Title: THE FOUR OLDS
Credit: v14 — full engine rebuild (bottom-up caper, rage-and-release, 1883 register)
Draft date: 2026-07-12 03:49

INT. CABLE NEWS STUDIO - NIGHT

A wall of monitors flips the electoral board from red to blue in a single second.

Balloons drop onto a news desk and bounce off the anchors' shoulders.

In the crowd, two people hold up a bedsheet painted with block letters.

ON THE SHEET -- HISTORY IS HEALING.

A COMMENTATOR, silver hair, wet eyes, stares into the lens and lets a tear sit there.

COMMENTATOR:
It's a reconciliation. With a whole world the last administration spent years insulting, and tonight that world is watching us come back to the table.

The camera finds a draped platform where MARWANI, 41, stands at the podium.

A UN flag rises beside the fifty stars at the same height.

MARWANI:
I do not stand here to celebrate a victory. I stand here to begin a repair.

MARWANI:
On behalf of the United States, to every nation we have wronged, we are sorry.

MARWANI:
This is not retreat. This is not surrender. This is repair.

The crowd rises and the applause runs long under a crawling chyron.

ON THE CHYRON -- NOBEL COMMITTEE AWARDS PEACE PRIZE, CITING "THE ANNOUNCED AGENDA."

The frame cuts to the belly of a military cargo plane, where shrink-wrapped pallets of banded hundred-dollar bills run the length of the bay.

A manifest is zip-tied to the nearest pallet, stamped in red.

ON THE MANIFEST -- IRAN COMPENSATION FRAMEWORK, DISBURSEMENT 1 OF 12.

A young STATE DEPARTMENT AIDE, 25, lanyard, turns his back to the money and lifts his phone for a selfie.

He checks the shot, frowns, and takes a better one.

The scene moves to a bright signing room in Brussels, where the Treasury Secretary signs the last page of a document as thick as a phone book.

Champagne pours and a stock ticker behind him runs all red.

ON THE TICKER -- AMERICA COMMITS $200 BILLION TO EUROPEAN DEFENSE RENEWAL.

A phone screen fills the frame with a push alert.

ON THE SCREEN -- WHITE HOUSE UNVEILS "STEWARDSHIP ACT": PRIVATE ASSETS ABOVE $1B TO BE ADMINISTERED IN THE PUBLIC INTEREST.

A thumb swipes it away and another alert lands in its place.

The picture opens on a Senate hearing room, where MAGNUS HALE, 50s, sits alone at the witness table with one printed page in front of him.

HALE:
Frontier is proud to serve the goals of this administration, at home and beyond it.

A SENATOR leans into his own microphone and holds the word in his mouth.

SENATOR:
Nationalization.

Hale folds his page in half, then folds it in half again, and looks at the Senator without a word.

The last cut lands inside Roy's Diner at morning, where six regulars sit along a counter while a muted TV over the pie case cycles the same footage from the montage.

A radio at the end of the counter murmurs at almost no volume, and nobody reaches for it.

RADIO (RADIO):
under the carbon framework the sale, use, and private storage of consumer fireworks is prohibited nationwide effective the first of the month, with the Department directing local surrender of existing —

EARLENE, 60s, works the pot down the counter and tops off Buck's cup without being asked.

BUCK, 70s, feed cap, watches the TV for a second and turns his cup a quarter turn on the saucer.

BUCK:
Huh.

He drinks.

The screen goes to black.

THE FOUR OLDS.

INT. FIRST PLAINS BANK, BROKEN BOW, NEBRASKA - DAY

A LOAN OFFICER, 30s, his tie still creased from the package, holds the phone to his shoulder and waves the old man toward the chair.

OFFICER:
No, that's the county's. The culvert out on the section line, that's not us. Tell him to call Roads.

OFFICER:
Yeah. The number's on their website somewhere. Alright. Bye.

CRICKET, 79, a seed-corn cap in his lap, sits down and squares a thick folder on his knees.

A cardboard sign leans in the window by the door and reads THE STEWARDSHIP ACT, WORKING FOR COMMUNITIES LIKE YOURS.

Cricket opens the folder. Tabs run down the edge in a straight line, one for every quarter, going back fifty years.

He takes the county letter off the top and lays it on the desk facing the officer.

CRICKET:
They reassessed the home place. I came about the sixty days.

The officer reads the letter, then types the account up on his screen.

OFFICER:
Forty-two oh six, due the fifteenth. Okay.

OFFICER:
And you're sitting at, what, twenty-one hundred in the checking.

CRICKET:
Twenty-one forty. As of the tenth.

OFFICER:
Right.

He clicks into another screen and slows down, reading it under his breath.

OFFICER:
There's a hardship program. There was. Let me just...

OFFICER:
It's paused. Not paused — there's no — there isn't a mechanism right now. Is what that means.

CRICKET:
Who do I talk to, then.

OFFICER:
That's the thing. It went federal in the spring. There's no office to send you to anymore, it just says pending review.

He scrolls the account history looking for a recent deposit and stops partway down.

OFFICER:
That's — hang on. You've got a payroll line on here.

A deposit near the bottom of the history reads NASA, $0.00 QUARTERLY.

The account description beside it reads DAWES, E., ASTRONAUT (ACTIVE).

OFFICER:
Zero dollars, every quarter, going back to seventy-two. And it's still marked active. I've never seen the system do that.

OFFICER:
I can scrub it for you while we're in here. It's just sitting there wrong anyway.

CRICKET:
Leave it.

The word comes out too fast. The officer's hand stops on the mouse.

CRICKET:
It's been there fifty years. It can stay.

The officer looks at him a second, then moves the cursor off the line and leaves it.

OFFICER:
Okay.

He opens a drawer and takes out a rubber date stamp.

OFFICER:
Our scanner's been down since Tuesday. So if your paperwork came in today and I couldn't scan it, it wouldn't post until next cycle.

He presses the stamp to the form and turns the page so Cricket can see the date.

OFFICER:
That buys you about sixty days. Don't tell my branch manager.

He peels the yellow carbon from the back of the form and slides it across the desk.

CRICKET:
What do I owe you.

OFFICER:
It's a bank, Mr. Dawes. You owe us four thousand dollars.

Cricket closes the folder, stands, and gets to the door before he stops.

CRICKET:
That culvert. On the section line.

OFFICER:
...Yeah?

CRICKET:
Route 12, out by the Hollen place. Log chain and a tractor'll do it. Hour of work.

He lifts two fingers off the folder without turning around and goes out the door.

The officer watches it swing shut, then turns back to the screen.

OFFICER:
...I'll pass that on. Every quarter, huh.

Outside, Cricket sits alone in the cab of his pickup. Through the windshield, the courthouse flag hangs across the street.

His shoulders come down half an inch and he lets out one long breath.

CRICKET:
"Working for communities like yours."

The corner of his mouth moves. He turns the key and the engine catches.

INT. DAWES BARN - NIGHT

A hand finds the pull-cord in the dark and the light comes on with a CLICK.

The bulb swings over an APOLLO PROCEDURES TRAINER built into the far end of the barn.

Hand-machined gauges crowd the panel, each dial cut and numbered by hand.

A crew couch sits bolted into a welded steel cradle in front of the panel.

A triangular window faces a Moon painted on the barn boards, gray and flat.

ALONG THE BACK WALL -- spiral notebooks stand floor to roof, every spine dated in the same block hand.

The bottom shelf starts in 1972.

CRICKET, 79, in a barn coat, lowers himself onto the couch and lifts a hand microphone off its hook.

He keys the mic.

CRICKET:
Net's open. Tuesday, nineteen-oh-two local.

The speaker answers first in a flat, dry voice.

DUTCH (RADIO):
Dutch is up. Got you loud.

A slow Texas drawl comes on behind him.

STITCH (RADIO):
Stitch is here. Settled in, coffee's hot, y'all take your time.

The last voice is clipped and Navy.

GUNNY (RADIO):
Tibbs, up and on time. Which is better than Texas managed.

GUNNY (RADIO):
It's nineteen-oh-three, gentlemen. Commander, run your checklist.

Cricket props a plastic card against the panel and works down it with one finger.

CRICKET:
Starting down.

He throws a row of toggles and the panel lights shift.

A needle on the panel drifts off its mark.

The buzz behind the panel stutters, drops, catches again.

CRICKET:
Needle's walking. Low left.

DUTCH (RADIO):
Steady, or does it stutter?

CRICKET:
Stutters.

DUTCH (RADIO):
That's Bus B. Same relay I put in in eighty-four.

STITCH (RADIO):
Here he goes.

DUTCH (RADIO):
I'm allowed to say it. Kick it, low left corner.

Cricket lifts his boot and raps the lower left corner of the panel with his heel.

The needle climbs back onto its mark and the buzz behind the panel smooths out.

He eases a lever down a notch and watches the altimeter unwind.

A blue lamp lights on the panel.

CRICKET:
Contact light. Engine stop.

He flips two switches and the buzz dies out.

For a moment nobody keys a mic and the barn holds still.

STITCH (RADIO):
Hair late on the throttle there at the end.

GUNNY (RADIO):
The man is on the ground, Colonel.

CRICKET:
Net closed. Same time Tuesday.

GUNNY (RADIO):
God willing.

Cricket presses the key twice, two short clicks.

Two clicks come back over the speaker. Then two more behind them.

He hangs the microphone on its hook and opens a fresh spiral notebook.

He writes in ballpoint block letters, and the page reads T+2,806. BUS B CORRECTED. CONTACT 19:41. CREW PRESENT BY RADIO.

He runs a thumb down the dated spines, from 1972 up to the shelf by his head.

He pulls the cord and the barn goes dark, then slides the door shut behind him.

He sets a padlock through the hasp and tests it with one pull.

Across the yard the farmhouse porch light burns over the steps.

Cricket crosses to it. No lights are on inside the house.

He climbs the steps and lets himself in.

INT. DAWES FARMHOUSE, KITCHEN - NIGHT

CRICKET, 79, sits alone at the kitchen table under one bulb, a pencil working down the margin of the county letter.

One plate stands in the dish rack. No second chair is pulled out from the table.

Through the doorway the front-room television plays with the sound off.

He carries a column of long division down the margin and writes the answer under a line.

The wall phone RINGS.

He sets the pencil down, crosses to it, and lifts the receiver off the hook.

CRICKET:
Dawes.

His son Danny is on the line, a kitchen going somewhere behind him.

DANNY:
It's me. You eat something?

CRICKET:
I did.

DANNY:
We finally got the beans in. Ground was still too wet down by the creek, but we got around it.

CRICKET:
Good.

DANNY:
They ran the fall calves through the sale barn Thursday. Did all right, better than last year anyhow. ...Rachel says hi. She keeps meaning to call you and then it gets to be nine o'clock.

CRICKET:
Tell her hello.

The line goes quiet a second. Behind Danny a chair scrapes and a door bumps shut.

DANNY:
Dad. Listen. Maybe don't watch the news tonight.

CRICKET:
Thank you for calling.

He hangs the receiver on the hook and stands there a moment.

He goes into the front room, sits in the armchair, and turns the sound up.

On the screen, President Marwani stands at a lectern in front of a pale blue flag.

MARWANI:
Tonight I am signing the Lunar Heritage Neutralization Accord.

MARWANI:
Fifty-seven years ago, one nation planted its banner on ground that belongs to all mankind. It stayed there through every apology we owed and never gave.

The picture cuts to the old photograph of an astronaut saluting the flag, next to a white shape with no color left in it.

A caption sits under the white one and reads ARTIST'S RENDERING, CURRENT CONDITION.

MARWANI:
Our own scientists tell us fifty years of sun have bleached all six of them to white. There is no color left in them at all.

MARWANI:
Some call those flags of surrender. I call them flags of peace.

MARWANI:
This coming July fourth, we will bring all six of them home, live, with one world watching. Not Independence Day. This year, the first Unity Day.

MARWANI:
And then we give them away. One flag to each nation this country has wronged. The first, to the people of Iran.

MARWANI:
In their place, our crew will plant the Harmony Banner, designed for us by a committee of forty-four nations.

The picture returns to the anchor desk, where two anchors nod along.

ANCHOR:
— being called the most generous act in the history of spaceflight.

Cricket sits still, the pencil turning slow between two fingers.

The pencil breaks in his hand with a small SNAP.

One half drops to the rug. He does not look down for it.

He turns the television off and sets the remote down square on the arm cover.

He goes to the kitchen phone, lifts the receiver, and dials seven numbers, then four more, without looking at his hand.

The line picks up. Dutch is there.

CRICKET:
You watching this?

DUTCH:
Both channels. They're running that white mock-up every ten minutes.

Neither man says anything for a moment.

CRICKET:
Tuesday. Early.

He sets the receiver back on the cradle, gently.

INT. FEDERAL COMPLIANCE FIELD OFFICE - DAY

PELL, 50s, a lanyard over a pressed shirt, sits squared to a monitor with his hands folded on the desk.

A wall map behind him holds red pins in a loose scatter, most of them east of where he sits.

A framed commendation photo stands on the sill, the little date plate on it two years old.

On the screen HOLLOWAY, 50s, works a second window while he talks, the picture running a half second behind his voice.

HOLLOWAY:
— you're at four verified, against a regional average sitting around eleven, and the broadcast's Saturday.

PELL:
I've got six others past intake and moving. They're sound. They're just sitting down at the lab waiting on the verification to come back.

HOLLOWAY:
The board's not counting anything that's still down at the lab.

PELL:
No, I hear you. Those'll clear, though, they always do, I've never had one come back on me in eleven —

HOLLOWAY:
The President's office pulled the regional list themselves this week. They asked for yours by name.

PELL:
Okay. That's good to know. I appreciate you telling me.

HOLLOWAY:
After Saturday I'm staffing up a couple regions and thinning out a couple others. Where you sit after that comes down to your number. You follow me.

A field radio on the credenza breaks in with a SQUAWK.

TWO-OH-FOUR (RADIO):
Office, two-oh-four. We're clear of the Halvorsen place, it's closed out. You want it filed today?

Pell taps mute on the call, lifts the radio handset, and turns his mouth away from the screen.

PELL (WHISPER):
Hold the Halvorsen close-out, don't file it yet, I want it on Saturday's count.

He sets the handset down, unmutes, and comes back to the screen.

PELL:
You'll see it move. I want this region whole for the board same as you do. I've got a north parcel I can take on myself, it's exactly the kind of thing that —

A second call flashes on Holloway's side and his eyes go to it.

HOLLOWAY:
Do that. I've got Grand Island holding.

The window closes with a chime before Pell finishes.

PELL:
— verifies clean.

The screen drops to the agency logo, and the office goes quiet under the radio hum.

Pell slides a printout from the tray, a FEDERAL ASSET LIST with one line run through in yellow.

The highlighted line names a surplus training unit signed out decades back and never sent home.

He stands, pulls a folder from the standing rack, its tab marked DAWES / FRONTIER.

He lays it open flat on the desk, under the lamp.

EXT. DAWES FARM - DAY

Two black SUVs come up the section road and stop short of the yard, and a county flatbed swings in behind them.

CRICKET, Earl Dawes, 79, gray work shirt buttoned to the collar, stands in the open barn doorway and stays up on the sill.

Back by the water trough the other three from the Tuesday crew stand and watch, Gunny and Stitch and Dutch, and they don't come any closer.

PELL, J. Pell, 50s, lanyard, a clipboard held flat to his chest, climbs out of the lead SUV smiling and takes in the barn.

WADE, Wade Halversen, mid-40s, county deputy, hat down in his hand, gets out of the flatbed last and hangs back by the fender.

Inside the barn sits THE TRAINER, a boxy Apollo cockpit mock-up bolted to the floor, worn bright at the hatch rail.

Pell walks in to it, clipboard up, and reads down the list without slowing.

PELL:
One seat, one hand controller, one altitude indicator—

CRICKET:
Attitude.

Pell stops, clicks his pen, and fixes the word on the sheet.

PELL:
Noted.

A mover peels an orange sticker off a roll and presses it to the trainer's flank, and Pell leans in and smooths it flat with his thumb.

ON THE STICKER -- LUNAR HERITAGE NEUTRALIZATION ACCORD, EX-NASA ASSET RECOVERY.

CRICKET:
It was surplus. Nineteen seventy-five. Told it'd be scrapped otherwise.

Pell doesn't look up from the clipboard.

PELL:
Paperwork says otherwise.

Two movers wheel a dolly up across the porch, and their boots leave gray scuffs on boards Cricket painted new.

One of them cracks a knuckle on the trainer's frame and shakes the hand out and swears low.

Cricket reaches to the pegboard without looking, takes down a socket, and holds it out, and the man takes it and can't look at him.

AT THE LOG WALL -- Pell runs a finger along fifty years of notebooks and pulls one out.

He opens it to three pages of grid-ruled block printing and turns them over.

PELL:
Personal papers.

He reads a second page, closes the cover, and drops the notebook back on the shelf crooked.

PELL:
No salvage value. Leave them.

Cricket watches the dolly get chained in under the trainer and speaks without turning around.

CRICKET:
Not one of you ever built a thing out here. Now it's all yours.

Pell stops writing and looks at him, and the recital goes out of his voice.

PELL:
You didn't build this either, Mr. Dawes. Nineteen seventy-five it was supposed to go back to NASA. It never did, and nobody came asking about it for fifty years. Sitting on a thing that long doesn't make it yours. It just means nobody came and took it back till now.

Cricket says nothing to that.

AT THE DOORWAY -- the dolly turns for the light, and Cricket steps down off the sill and puts himself square in the opening.

The movers stop. Pell looks over to Wade.

CRICKET:
You'll have to move me, Wade.

Wade sets his hat on the workbench and comes across the barn slow.

WADE:
Earl.

He takes Cricket by both shoulders, gentle, and walks him three steps to the side, and Cricket lets him.

The dolly rolls out past the two of them into the yard with the trainer on it.

Where it stood, a clean rectangle shows in the dust, four bolt holes at the corners.

Cricket keeps his eyes on the trainer going up the flatbed ramp, and Wade stays in close beside him, voice down.

CRICKET:
Where's it go.

WADE:
Warehouse outside Lincoln, is what I hear. Same one as the rest of it.

WADE:
Federal list come down Tuesday, Earl. County don't see a dime off any of it. Nobody does.

Cricket doesn't answer, and Wade turns his hat brim in his fingers.

WADE:
There's a form, if you want to file it. Office over in Grand Island. It's open till four today.

Pell signs the last page, tears off a pink copy, and lays it on the workbench.

He turns to the yard and puts the smile back on for the old men at the trough.

PELL:
Folks, I know change feels sudden. But as the Accord reminds us — harmony is a verb.

He gets in the lead SUV and pulls the door shut.

The SUVs turn around in the yard, and the flatbed follows them out down the section road.

Cricket walks back into the barn and stops at the edge of the dust rectangle.

He puts one hand to the back of his neck and presses hard, takes one breath, and straightens up.

On the bench the radio the movers left behind plays low, a farm report half lost in static.

The other three come in off the fence and stand around the empty floor with him.

CRICKET:
Net's open. Wednesday.

The answers come back quick, before he's done.

GUNNY:
I'll bring the grill.

STITCH:
Same as always.

DUTCH:
Nineteen hundred.

Gunny reaches up and pulls the chain on the work light over the bench, and it comes on.

INT. DAWES BARN - NIGHT

The work light over the bench throws the only light in the barn, and the floor where the trainer stood sits bare.

GUNNY Tibbs, 71, Navy retired, hauls a cardboard case up onto the bench and folds the flaps back off a row of mortar tubes.

Cricket stands at the edge of the empty rectangle with his hands in his back pockets and watches him do it.

GUNNY:
I did two years on a missile submarine off Alaska, listening for Soviet propellers, so men like Earl could keep a barn a Russian couldn't touch. And a fella in a zip-up vest walks in with a sticker gun.

STITCH McGrew, 74, leans on the far end of the bench with a lighter turning over in his fingers.

DUTCH Haas, 76, stands off to the side with his binder shut under one arm.

GUNNY:
Commies. Don't care what flag they're flying over the building.

Dutch sets the binder down on the bench and leaves it closed.

DUTCH:
Seventy-five, I hauled that thing up from Houston in a borrowed horse trailer. Supply captain signed it out and said if the truck showed up empty, empty's what the truck would show. Fifty years I kept government property safe for the government. They sent a man to take it back like I stole it.

STITCH:
I still got four cases of the three-inch mortars out in the shed. Bought 'em a good two years before anybody thought to ban a firework.

GUNNY:
Compliance office locks up at five. Whole lot's empty gravel come dark. Nobody's parked in it since they poured it.

CRICKET:
That's a federal building.

GUNNY:
It's a strip mall with a flagpole, Earl.

Cricket picks one of the mortar tubes up off the bench, turns it over once, and sets it back down where it was.

CRICKET:
I've got a grandson who still thinks I hung the moon. Not explaining a courtroom to him. Count me out.

Gunny folds the flaps back down over the case and holds it shut with one hand.

GUNNY:
Rest of us, then. Friday.

Cricket crosses to the door and stops with his hand flat on the frame.

CRICKET:
Do what you're going to do. Just don't tell me about it after.

The compliance office sits dark behind a wide gravel lot, with one flagpole out front and no flag on it.

The three of them stand in the middle of the gravel in no hurry, a case open at their feet.

Stitch touches the lighter to the first tube and steps back.

The shell climbs and lights the lot red, then green, then hangs a long gold over the roofline.

The crack rolls back off the storefronts a second behind it.

A county cruiser rolls in slow with its bar lights off, and Wade gets out with his hand nowhere near his holster.

Wade looks up at the sky first, then back down at the three of them.

WADE:
Y'all want to tell me whose idea this was, or should I guess?

GUNNY:
Mine.

DUTCH:
His, but I brought the truck.

STITCH:
I just held the lighter. Following orders.

The county courtroom sits near empty in the morning light, and the three men stand at the front table in clean shirts.

JUDGE BENNING, 70s, reading glasses down his nose, looks up from the file at them.

BENNING:
How do you plead.

GUNNY:
Guilty.

DUTCH:
Same.

STITCH:
Guilty, your honor.

The file open in front of Benning lists a scorched patch of gravel and not one person hurt.

BENNING:
I was nine years old in my daddy's living room the night men from this state walked on the Moon. Watched it on a television the size of a bread box. Time served. Four hundred dollars each, plus the cost of the gravel. I've got real criminals on this morning's docket, gentlemen. Get on home.

The prosecutor comes half up out of his chair, and the gavel comes down before he gets a word out.

Cricket waits at the bottom of the courthouse steps with his truck at the curb behind him.

The three come down the steps, and Gunny reaches him first.

GUNNY:
Come to gloat?

CRICKET:
Came to drive you home.

Stitch and Dutch go on past toward the truck, and the two of them stand there a second.

GUNNY:
You could've come.

CRICKET:
I know it.

Gunny claps him once, hard, on the shoulder and heads for the truck.

INT. ROY'S DINER - DAY

A gray COUNTY METER hangs zip-tied to the gas line behind the counter, its little numbers ticking up.

THE COOK, 60s, works the flat-top with his back to the room and cuts a look at the meter.

COOK:
Yeah, I see you.

A county letter is taped up by the register, one line on it circled in pen, WEEKLY ALLOWANCE.

The Cook reads it the once and goes back to the eggs without a word.

On the wall TV a loft full of matching UNITY DAY shirts cheers a countdown clock.

A crawl runs under the picture and reads 62 DAYS TO UNITY DAY, NATIONS OF HONOR ANNOUNCED FRIDAY.

A panelist talks over the white rendering of the flags.

PANELIST:
— this is a president finishing an argument America started losing in 1969—

BUCK, 70s, in a feed cap, sits over a coffee at the counter with his eyes on the screen.

EARLENE, 60s, works the till down the counter with the pot in her hand.

Buck says it into his coffee, not loud.

BUCK:
Fifty years we kept commies off the Moon. All they had to do was win a primary.

Earlene doesn't look up from the register.

EARLENE:
Buck.

BUCK:
I said it quiet.

The Cook picks up the remote and flips over to the ball game.

On the broadcast a public-address voice comes up over the ballpark.

PA (RADIO):
Please rise for tonight's anthem, One World Rising, performed by the Children's Harmony Choir.

On the screen some of the crowd stands. A lot of it doesn't.

The Cook turns the sound down, not off.

Buck starts humming into his coffee, and four notes in it's the old anthem.

The Cook's spatula picks up the time against the edge of the grill, small, maybe not on purpose.

Earlene hums the next bar while she counts a stranger's change.

Nobody stands up, and nobody looks at anybody else.

The verse ends, and the counter goes back to forks and plates.

Down the counter Wade sits in uniform over a plate of eggs, his hat set crown-up beside him.

His coffee cup has been empty a while.

Earlene wipes the counter three feet from the pot and doesn't reach for it.

Wade doesn't look at the cup again. He slides two dollars under the saucer and takes his hat.

The bell over the door rings behind him.

CRICKET, 79, comes in and takes the end stool, and Earlene sets coffee down before he's square on the seat.

Buck slides the sugar caddy over within his reach without looking up from his plate.

Cricket goes for his wallet, and Earlene is already wiping past him.

EARLENE:
It's paid.

CRICKET:
Obliged.

He puts his cap on, and the bell rings as he goes out.

Through the window the courthouse flag stands across the square.

The meter ticks up another number. The Cook watches it a second and turns back to the grill.

EXT. COUNTY CEMETERY - DAY

A small county cemetery sits off a gravel lane, a chain-link fence around mown grass gone brown at the tips.

CRICKET, 79, comes up a row of stones with a fist of zinnias and stops at one.

DUTCH, 76, follows a step behind with his cap held in both hands.

Cricket lowers down and brushes the grass clippings off the top of the stone with the side of his hand.

The stone reads PEG DAWES.

CRICKET:
Peg had these all down the fence line. Orange ones, mostly.

He works the stems into a canning jar and turns it so the wind won't take it over.

Dutch stays off the corner of the plot, turning the cap in his hands.

DUTCH:
When'd she start in on Marwani.

CRICKET:
First time the man was ever on the television. Watched him maybe a minute and said he was selling something. Never trusted him a day after. And you know she had a kind word for about everybody.

DUTCH:
Before he ever had the county, then.

CRICKET:
Long before. Made her mind up right there in the front room and never went back on it.

Dutch fits his cap back on and looks at the stone a while.

Cricket presses the jar down into the grass until it stands on its own.

INT. AMERICAN LEGION POST 219, BACK ROOM - NIGHT

A wood stove ticks in the corner of the Legion back room, and a row of folding chairs stands squared up against the paneling.

Unit photographs hang along the wall in cheap frames, the oldest of them back to Korea.

MACK Boone, 55, freight hauler, sets a thin folder on the card table and slides one sheet halfway out of it.

Cricket, Gunny, Stitch, and Dutch sit around the table with coffee going cold in front of them.

MACK:
Read that before I say a word. Then you can throw me out if you want.

Mack pushes the top sheet to the middle of the table.

ON THE MANIFEST -- LUNAR HERITAGE NEUTRALIZATION ACCORD, ARTIFACT RETRIEVAL. SIX (6) CONTAINMENT UNITS, CLASS-A ARCHIVAL. OUTBOUND CONFIGURATION, EMPTY.

Dutch picks the manifest up and reads the whole of it twice before he puts it down.

DUTCH:
Six boxes. They go up empty.

MACK:
And they come back down with the flags in them.

Nobody says anything, and the stove ticks.

Mack turns the sheet over to a printed email and reads it off with no color in his voice at all.

MACK:
Containment units are non-crew hardware. No certification pathway required. Recommend sourcing retired fabrication and aerospace personnel at heritage-labor rates.

He sets the page down where they can all see it.

MACK:
Heritage-labor rates. That's you, gentlemen. That's this whole room.

Stitch turns his cup a quarter turn on the table and looks at the email.

STITCH:
Cheap old men. To box up the—

He lets it drop, and not one man at the table picks it up for him.

Dutch has the spec page out of his own packet already and runs a thumb down the margin.

DUTCH:
This is my standard. The '98 archival spec. Word for word.

MACK:
Nobody's improved it.

Gunny stands, squares his chair back against the wall, and stays on his feet.

GUNNY:
Somebody's going to fold those colors into them, on live television, with the whole world grading the job. I'd sooner it be men who know how a flag is handled than whoever else answers that email. We're the whoever-else, boys.

A short, hard laugh goes around the table and dies out fast.

Mack deals a stapled packet to each man like he's dealing cards, and only Dutch reads all of his.

Mack taps the last page with one finger.

MACK:
No phones in the shop, no pictures. And whatever gets built in there, it stays inside those walls.

Stitch signs his without turning past the first page.

STITCH:
Confidential flag boxes.

MACK:
That's the job.

Gunny signs, and Dutch signs under him, slow, down at the bottom of the last page.

Cricket slides his own packet back to the middle with no mark on it, puts his cap on, and gets up.

The back door BANGS behind him.

Nobody moves, and Gunny pours a cup off the percolator he doesn't drink.

A minute later the door opens and Cricket comes back in with the cap still on his head.

He takes his packet up off the table, turns to the spec page, and reads it standing where he is.

He picks up the pen and signs last, at the bottom, under Dutch.

CRICKET:
When's Monday.

INT. FRONTIER AEROSPACE, FABRICATION BAY 2 - DAY

MIRA VESS, 40s, in a dark suit, stands on the bay floor in front of the whole shift in company blues.

The ranks stand with their welding hoods pushed up and their gloves off.

PELL, 50s, waits off to one side with a tablet and a lanyard, thumbing at notes.

VESS:
Bay Two closes today. Every one of you is paid twelve months at full rate, and your medical stays on the whole time.

A woman starts down the rows handing a printed card to each man.

VESS:
There's a card coming to you. It puts you first in line if this floor ever runs again.

VESS:
I don't expect you to believe that means anything. Keep the card anyway.

A WORKER near the front steps out of his row.

WORKER:
My father cut the first nozzle ring in this bay!

VESS:
I know he did. His name is on the wall of the visitor center.

VESS:
The tooling gets declared surplus and sold at public auction. An outside outfit comes in to pallet it up and count it.

At the back wall, MACK BOONE, 55, unfolds his arms at that.

VESS:
Whatever you need to think about today, put it on me.

Pell steps in at her shoulder with the tablet up.

PELL:
The Monitorship views this as a — a meaningful posture of alignment. I'll be noting the, ah, expedited timeline favorably.

VESS:
Note whatever you like.

She walks out, and her heels on the concrete are the only sound in the bay.

Later, the bay doors stand open to the lot, and men carry toolboxes and milk crates out past a news crew at the fence.

On a bench sits a practice weld, two steel plates joined by one bead so even there's no start or stop you can find in it.

TITO, 24, in a welder's jacket, latches his toolbox and picks up his hood.

Mack stops at the bench, looks at the weld a moment, then at Tito.

MACK:
Keep your tools.

TITO:
I just got fired, Mr. Boone.

MACK:
I know what happened. Keep your tools.

Tito lifts his box and goes.

Mack takes a small notebook from his shirt pocket and writes one line in it.

INT. FEDERAL BUILDING, WASHINGTON - CONFERENCE ROOM - DAY

A long table fills the conference room, and a dozen senior staffers sit down both sides with notepads and water glasses.

HOLLOWAY, 50s, stands at the head with a thin folder in his hand.

PELL, 50s, sits near the foot in his good jacket, his lanyard squared on his chest.

HOLLOWAY:
Last thing. The Unity Day recovery needs a lead out front, and it needs somebody who closes clean. Eleven years, nobody in this building closes cleaner than Pell.

HOLLOWAY:
The Nebraska parcel last month, the aerospace pull, that was him. Exactly the kind of rigor this program's been missing.

HOLLOWAY:
So. Special Administrator, Lunar Heritage Recovery. That's you.

HOLLOWAY:
You'd be out front on it, the press, the whole artifact side. And nothing ships that day without your sign-off. Congratulations.

Down both sides of the table, the senior staff find something to read on their notepads at the same moment.

Holloway looks down the table at WHITFIELD, a senior staffer with a full calendar open in front of her.

HOLLOWAY:
Whitfield, your shop want in on the artifact side, or --

WHITFIELD:
Scheduling conflict.

Pell sits up as Holloway slides the folder down the table to him.

PELL:
Thank you. I mean it. Eleven years, I always told myself the work was the thing, you don't do it to get—

PELL:
I won't let the Accord down.

Nobody looks up at him. At the far end a staffer squares a fresh stack of agendas and slides the top one to her neighbor.

HOLLOWAY:
Good. That's the hour. Whitfield, walk with me.

Holloway is already at the door, and someone holds it open for him a beat too fast.

Pell gathers the folder up in both hands and goes out after them.

In the corridor he stops alone at a lit trophy case along the wall.

He straightens his lanyard in the dark glass over the awards, then goes on down the hall.

EXT. TRI-COUNTY AUCTION BARN - DAY

A bank of sodium lamps BANGS on over an empty auction floor, then a second bank, then the last one down at the far end.

A gantry crane runs the length of the ceiling on a worn rail.

A scale pit sits sunk into the middle of the floor, and two loading docks stand open to the daylight at the far end.

MACK Boone, 55, freight hauler, walks the crew in through a roll-up door with a cardboard tube of drawings under his arm.

MACK:
Client's a federal contract and a county landlord. Cheaper than a real shop.

Stitch, the Texan, turns a slow circle in the middle of the floor with his hands on his hips.

STITCH:
Smells like about forty years of hog auction in here.

Cricket walks to the edge of the scale pit, looks down into it, and looks up at the crane rail.

CRICKET:
Crane still swings. Pit's dry.

Gunny sets an empty coffee can down on the first workbench and holds it out as each man comes past.

GUNNY:
Son. Phones.

JOSS Reed, 26, still in his Frontier dock vest, stops with his hands down in his pockets.

JOSS:
It's a WATCH.

GUNNY:
Can, son.

Joss unclasps the watch and drops it in with the rest.

TITO Alvarez, 24, a welder's cap pushed back off his face, drops his own phone in the can before Gunny gets to him.

Dutch, the oldest man there, unrolls a set of drawings across two sawhorses and weights the corners down with sockets.

ON THE TITLE BLOCK -- LUNAR HERITAGE NEUTRALIZATION ACCORD, CONTRACT NO. HRT-2049-6.

DUTCH:
Six of them, all the same. The flag rides flat inside. We pull the air out, bake the moisture off the fabric, then put nitrogen in so the dye doesn't rot on the way up.

Tito leans over the drawing and sets one finger on a corner of the interior frame.

TITO:
You called this weld out full through, all the way. That much heat's going to cook the fitting and pull it out of true.

TITO:
Move it here. Come in under the frame rail. Nobody ever sees it.

Dutch picks the pencil up off the paper, looks at the spot under Tito's finger, and holds the pencil out to him.

Tito takes it and walks the line two inches over on the drawing.

Joss drags a stack of steel sheet off a pallet at the back and talks without looking up from it.

JOSS:
So we build fake ones and switch them, right. The flags never come down.

Mack keeps dealing contract packets out along the bench and doesn't turn around.

MACK:
The play is we build six containment units to federal spec and deliver them on time. It's a job, son.

Joss goes back to the steel.

Dutch runs a tape down the inside of the first frame and writes the length in his binder, then stops with the pen on the page.

DUTCH:
Interior's awful generous for cloth.

Tito keeps his tape on the frame and does not look up.

TITO:
Man could about fit in there.

Joss looks over from the steel at the back.

JOSS:
How would a person even ride in a box.

Gunny checks the needle on a pressure gauge at the next bench and answers without turning around.

GUNNY:
Most of it's already there. Air in, breath scrubbed back out. I kept ninety men breathing under the ice for two years.

Mack looks up from the packets and points Stitch and Cricket toward the far bay.

MACK:
Cutting table's in Bay Two. Let's get the first frame tacked before lunch.

Tito carries the frame across to Bay Two and snaps a chalk line, then draws the outline of the crate on the bare concrete.

By the end of the day the first frame stands tacked together on the chalk marks.

The sodium lamps bang off row by row down the ceiling, and the last one leaves the chalk outline of the crate on the floor.

Mack tugs the roll-up door down with the coffee can of phones under his arm.

INT. FRONTIER AEROSPACE, TRAINING ROOM B - DAY

FACILITATOR is 30s, all teeth, a clicker in her hand. She thumbs the lights down to half.

The projector throws a slide on the wall. It reads 1966, A BOLD QUESTION, WHAT DO WE OWE THE PAST.

FACILITATOR:
Okay, so, Module Seven. This one's more of a conversation than the other ones, so bear with me.

She clicks. Four categories load on a soft harmony-blue background.

MACK is 55, with a freight man's hands. He copies the four names onto a legal pad in slow block letters.

BAY TWO MAN is 60s, in a clean shirt he ironed. He raises his hand about halfway.

BAY TWO MAN:
So one of these here. What actually counts as one of them. What's one of them look like.

FACILITATOR:
Great question. Honestly, great, and it's the one everybody kind of gets hung up on the first time.

FACILITATOR:
So the thing is you already know a bunch of them. The team names, the mascots, a lot of those came down a few years back and, honestly, the sky didn't fall.

Mack keeps printing the fourth name, not looking up.

FACILITATOR:
The schools that got renamed, that was a big one. Some of the holidays too. The statues, a lot of towns took those down and life just kind of went on.

FACILITATOR:
The Pledge, even. District by district, we've mostly moved past that one and nobody really made a thing of it.

FACILITATOR:
You had the whole beef conversation a while back. The appliance conversation. You lived through both of those.

FACILITATOR:
Cursive's a good one, actually. Schools just quit teaching it. Nobody voted on it or anything, and then one day the grandkids can't read a letter their grandmother wrote them.

FACILITATOR:
And that fireworks thing back in January, that's this exact framework, just applied at national scale. And it went fine.

FACILITATOR:
So nobody's gonna hand you a list. That's kind of the whole point. You already know what yours are, everybody in this room does, and the reflection piece just walks you through deciding what counts, for you.

Bay Two Man's hand comes down. He looks at the blank pad in front of him and doesn't write anything.

FACILITATOR:
And you can feel everybody kind of going inward with it right now. That's the work happening.

JOSS is 26, back row, in a dock hand's jacket, his chair tipped onto two legs. He watches the slide.

JOSS:
What happened to the people who liked the old stuff.

FACILITATOR:
So there were some implementation errors, in that era. Which is honestly why the frameworks now, they really center on dialogue.

The door opens. PELL steps in, 50s, a lanyard and a visitor badge. He stands at the back and beams at the wall.

PELL:
Centuries of ancient Chinese wisdom in that slide.

FACILITATOR:
Oh, it's from 1966—

PELL:
Wonderful.

Pell folds his hands and stays where he is.

She clicks. The new slide reads YOUR REFLECTION HOMEWORK, IDENTIFY ONE OLD HABIT YOU'RE READY TO RETIRE.

A clipboard starts down the front row, a pen chained to it, the sign-in sheet already half full of names.

Joss lets his chair down, takes the clipboard, and signs under the last name.

Joss and Mack come out into the corridor with the rest of the crowd.

JOSS (WHISPER):
My grandpa's old habit was getting shot at over Hanoi.

MACK:
Write coffee. Everybody writes coffee.

EXT. FIRST METHODIST CHURCH, BROKEN BOW - SUNDAY MORNING

Morning light falls on the front of First Methodist Church in Broken Bow, and a white county van sits at the curb with its back doors standing open.

A WORK ORDER hangs taped to the church door, a printed decibel allowance running under the county seal.

Two workers lean a ladder against the steeple and climb up toward the bell.

One of them fits a wrench onto the bolts that hold the clapper.

A small brass plaque sits by the door. It reads IN MEMORY, ORGAN FUND, and the name under it is worn too smooth to make out.

The organ comes faint through the wall, somewhere in the middle of a hymn.

The clock reaches the hour and the bell stays quiet.

The workers wrap the bell in canvas and cinch the straps down over it.

The steeple stands there with nothing coming out of it.

Out front of American Legion Post 219, WADE HALVERSEN gets out of the cruiser, mid-40s, a county star on his chest, his hat already down in his hand.

Three men in ball caps sit on the concrete steps under the flagpole.

Wade comes up with one folded permit and holds it out to the man closest to him.

WADE:
Morning, Tom. It's the flag one, the yearly permit. They sent it back not cleared this time.

The stamp where the fee used to go reads DENIED, PENDING HERITAGE REVIEW.

The man takes the paper and looks at it and doesn't say anything back.

WADE:
I just bring 'em around. You fellas take it easy.

Wade walks back to the cruiser with his eyes down on his own copy of it.

Behind him a younger man stands up and unclips the rope from the pole.

Night now in Danny's kitchen outside Kearney, where DANNY DAWES stands at the counter, 50, still in his work jacket, going through a stack of school papers.

A glass of milk sits half drunk next to an empty chair.

He turns over a worksheet headed MY HERITAGE JOURNEY, ONE FAMILY TRADITION I'M READY TO RETIRE.

Down on the answer line, in pencil block letters, it reads THE 4TH OF JULY COOKOUT AT GRANDPAS.

Danny reads it. He reads it again.

He sets the sheet down flat on the counter and squares the edge with his thumb.

He looks over at the empty chair and doesn't call the boy back in.

INT. TRI-COUNTY AUCTION BARN - DAY

The auction barn runs full. Bay Two men work their stations down the frame rail, and the cash box sits open on a stool by the door.

TITO ALVAREZ, 24, a welder's hood pushed up on his forehead, lays a bead down the seam of a crate clamped in the welding jig.

The bead runs even the whole length of the seam.

Purge lines run neat along the underside of the rail, tucked back where nobody will ever look.

GUNNY TIBBS, 71, a Navy ballcap on, moves down the row and looks at every man's work without stopping.

Tito sits wedged against the tank now, a wind-up watch open in his hand, waiting on the gauge.

He raps the steel twice. He waits. He raps it twice more.

Two knocks come back from inside the tank.

DUTCH HAAS, 76, reads the needle and writes a figure in a binder without looking up.

TITO:
Needle hasn't moved off it.

DUTCH:
Twelve hundred. Give it the four minutes and it logs.

ON THE SCREEN -- a helicopter holds a steady frame on the booster laid out full length on its transporter.

Fifty feet of painted stars and stripes runs the side of it.

A cherry-picker rides up alongside. Two painters roll white primer down the flag, top to bottom, one pass at a time.

The primer goes over the stars. The frame does not cut away.

The anchor has stopped talking.

The picture cuts to a Frontier press room, where a press row is leaning in toward a podium.

MIRA VESS, 40s, dark suit, no notes, steps up to the podium and settles the room with a look.

A reporter in the front row lifts a pen.

REPORTER:
Whose call was the paint?

VESS:
Mine. I ordered the repainting.

VESS:
The Accord specifies neutral mission livery. Paint is cheaper than a receiver. That math is my job.

The reporter is already halfway to the next one.

REPORTER:
Did Hale sign off on --

VESS:
The board meets Thursday. Bring it.

She gives the room a small even smile and steps back off the podium.

The picture cuts to the counter at Roy's Diner, where the same footage plays on the set bolted over the grill, the painters still rolling.

The COOK reaches up past the shelf and turns the set OFF.

The screen goes black. He turns back to the grill.

EARLENE, 60s, works the counter with the pot in her hand.

BUCK, 70s, feed cap, sits the far stool with a ball game going on the little set down at his end.

The door opens. EARL 'CRICKET' DAWES, 79, comes in and takes the third stool, the one that's his.

The sugar caddy stays where it is, by the napkins.

Earlene tops off a cup two stools down. She works her way back and gets to Cricket last.

She sets a coffee in front of him and moves off down the counter.

A ball cracks off a bat on Buck's set. Buck watches it carry.

Earlene tears a slip off her pad and lays it face down by Cricket's cup.

THE TICKET sits there, face down on the counter.

Cricket turns it over and reads it.

He counts coins onto the counter, one at a time, and sets them by the cup.

The coffee sits where she put it, gone cold.

He puts his cap on and goes out the door.

INT. TRI-COUNTY AUCTION BARN, LOADING DOCK - DAY

Two men lean against the roll-up door, a bay of light behind them, the yard beyond gone to heat-shimmer.

This is STITCH. Elmore 'Stitch' McGrew, 74, grease worked into the creases of his hands, a paper cup of water going warm in one of them.

Cricket drinks. Says nothing. Watches a forklift park itself two lots over.

STITCH:
You ever heard of Sky King?

CRICKET:
Can't say I have.

Stitch turns the cup a slow quarter-turn and looks out at the shimmer.

STITCH:
Fella up in Washington. Worked the airport, loaded the bags on and off the planes, that was the whole of his job. Never flew a one of 'em. Wasn't a pilot, wasn't studyin' to be, none of that.

A forklift beeps somewhere down the row, backing up, and quits.

STITCH:
Had one of them computer things at his kitchen table. The flyin' game, you know the kind. And he'd sit there of an evening and fly it. Years, I heard. Just at the table, after the kids or whoever, I don't know his whole business.

Cricket tips the cup back, finds it near empty, lets his arm hang.

CRICKET:
Then what happened.

STITCH:
Well, one mornin' he just walked on out there. Weren't nobody on the plane, mind, empty, a big ol' airliner. And he got in it and he took it up.

Stitch lifts his free hand off the door, level, and rolls it flat over, once.

STITCH:
Got her up over the mountains and rolled her clean around. The whole way over. Like you'd do a little one, and this a airliner, and him never flew a day.

Cricket has stopped drinking. His eyes stay on the far lot.

STITCH:
They sent the fighter jets up after him, quick as they could, to box him in and get him down. Two of 'em, I think, come up alongside.

A beat. Stitch drinks.

STITCH:
He just waved at 'em.

The heat holds. Neither man moves for a moment.

CRICKET:
What happened to him.

STITCH:
Never flew again, of course.

Stitch drains the cup, crumples it, pushes off the door.

STITCH:
All right. Let's get them chairs on the truck.

EXT. PIONEER FIELD, MINOR-LEAGUE BALLPARK - NIGHT

Pioneer Field sits packed under the lights, nine thousand people filling a minor-league park to the top row.

The public address voice comes up warm over the crowd.

PA (RADIO):
Please rise now for tonight's unity performance, One World Rising, brought to you by the Tri-Cities Children's Harmony Choir.

Down on the grass a children's choir files into its rows, and a young director lifts her hands to them.

A synthesizer and a run of chimes start up under the choir.

The crowd gets to its feet slow, hands staying down in their pockets.

Along the third-base line BUCK stands in his feed cap, 70s, looking past the choir to the flag out on the center field pole.

Buck takes his cap off and holds it, and he opens his mouth and starts to sing.

BUCK:
Oh, say can you see...

He is off the note and too loud, and for four bars he is the only voice in the park.

The row behind him picks it up, a couple of voices, then the whole row of them.

The section around him comes in after that, ragged and out of time with itself.

It carries back to the far bleachers, thousands of them now, none together and all of them going.

The synthesizer and the chimes keep playing underneath it, buried and steady.

Up on the concourse a COMPLIANCE KID stands at the rail, 20s, a lanyard at his neck, his tablet half raised toward the stands.

He looks down at the tablet, then out at the crowd, then down at the tablet again.

He lowers it and slides it inside his jacket.

Down on the grass the choir director lets her hands come down.

She turns her back on the choir and faces the flag out in center field.

Over in the next section CRICKET DAWES stands with his cap down at his side, 79, watching the rows behind home plate find the words a section at a time.

GUNNY TIBBS holds at attention beside him, 71, his thumb laid flat down the seam of his trousers.

DUTCH HAAS keeps his cap flat over the center of his chest, 76, and his mouth stays closed.

STITCH stands on past them, 74, hat in his hand, not singing.

A full row of empty seats runs along both sides of them in the sold-out park.

DANNY DAWES stands at his father's shoulder, 50, and he is singing it, plain and steady.

On the scoreboard a line reads TONIGHT'S POST-GAME LIGHT SHOW BROUGHT TO YOU BY THE UNITY FUND.

Two rows down a boy tugs his father's sleeve and points up at the board.

BOY:
Is the light show the one with the booms?

FATHER:
Not anymore, bud.

The last word carries up out of the park and dies off somewhere over the parking lots.

The crowd sits back down in sections and the game gets going.

The first pitch comes in and the umpire calls a strike.

The four of them look down the row at each other.

One by one they put their caps back on.

INT. ROY'S DINER - DAY

The frontier shop sits quiet in the TV corner, day light coming gray through the roll door.

A phone lies face-down on the workbench. JOSS, 26, dock gloves shoved in a back pocket, puts his thumb on it and slides it under a shop rag.

JOSS:
You don't have to look at it.

TITO, 24, welder's beanie, a cold coffee gone skin on top, keeps sorting torch tips and doesn't look up.

TITO:
Already did.

JOSS:
When.

TITO:
Lita sent it. Like five in the morning. She thought it was real nice, everybody singing.

The shop TV bolted over the parts shelf runs the morning show with the sound turned low.

On the screen a smiling ANCHOR sits over a still of the diner counter mid-song.

ANCHOR:
A whole room of them, singing right along. A charming, if off-key, moment out of, where's that, Deb, Nebraska someplace.

The clip goes to a split screen. A young couple lip-syncs a bit over the top of the old voices, mugging at the beat where the men go flat.

STITCH, 74, easy in a folding chair with a rag over his knee, watches it all the way through. DUTCH, 76, stands beside him with a binder shut under his arm.

The clip ends and loops. Nobody says anything to it.

Dutch turns and clicks the bench light back on over his work. Stitch picks his rag up off his knee.

STITCH:
Tips are the eight-fifties, if you're hunting.

Joss looks at the phone under the rag and leaves it there.

Roy's Diner runs its slow mid-morning down the length of the counter.

EARLENE, 60s, the coffee pot in one hand, works the stools. GUNNY, 71, Navy ball cap, runs the grill behind her. BUCK, 70s, feed cap, sits the third stool with his cup down.

A KID, early twenties, holds his phone out at arm's length in booth three and pans it slow across the room.

KID:
Booth three, real ones only, boomer diner check. Rent's up two hundred bucks this month and these guys are in here worked up about a song.

A COURIER pushes in with an insulated bag, crosses straight to booth three, and sets a foil burrito on the kid's table.

The kid takes the burrito without looking up and keeps the phone panning.

Earlene watches the courier go back out the door. She steps down the counter and fills Buck's cup to the line, and says nothing.

BUCK:
Weather's supposed to turn Thursday.

The TV over the pie case cuts to the same anchor, and Gunny reaches up and thumbs the volume.

ANCHOR:
More on the goodwill program this morning. The Accord's adding to it, they'll be sending a museum suit along with every flag now, one for one.

On the screen a graphic builds. An Apollo pressure suit stands on a mannequin with a small flag set at its boot.

ANCHOR:
The first one, flag and all, goes to the people of Iran.

Gunny sets the spatula down flat on the grill and leaves it. Buck's cup stays on the counter. Earlene holds the pot where she's standing and doesn't pour.

Night fills the barn, and the radio rig glows on the bench.

CRICKET, 79, feed-store jacket zipped to the throat, drags a stool up square to it and sits.

He keys the mic.

CRICKET:
Net's open. Tuesday, nineteen-oh-two local.

Static comes up out of the speaker and holds.

He waits. Nobody answers.

He waits longer. The static runs on by itself.

CRICKET:
Same time Tuesday.

He reaches up over his head and pulls the LIGHT CORD, and the barn goes black.

INT. TRI-COUNTY AUCTION BARN - NIGHT

The auction barn runs quiet under the sodium lamps, and the crew stands close around a last steel crate clamped in the jig.

JOSS raps the crate wall twice, waits, and raps it twice more, 26, his ear laid against the steel.

From inside the crate two knocks answer him.

The gauge on the frame climbs up to its mark and sits there without a drift.

TITO lifts the lid from the inside and climbs out with the wind-up watch still running in his hand, 24.

DUTCH stands at the workbench over the federal completion sheet, 76, and signs the bottom line.

He squares the paper to the edge of the bench with two fingers.

On the chalkboard by the door somebody has already put up TRUCKS 7 AM.

Dutch looks down the row of crates with the pencil still in his hand and doesn't set it down anywhere.

Six finished crates stand in a row under the lamps and nobody moves for a while.

CRICKET crosses to the fourth crate down, 79, and sits on the open edge of it.

He leans down and starts working his bootlaces loose.

CRICKET:
Somebody time me getting in. We'll want a number.

Tito steps over and knocks the crate wall twice with a knuckle.

TITO:
She'll hold.

GUNNY goes to the parts shelf, 71, and counts the air cartridges off it into rows of four.

He marks the shelf edge under each row with a grease pencil.

STITCH climbs up into the next crate over, 74, lies back in it, and sets his hat down on his chest.

STITCH:
Snug.

Dutch opens the binder to a clean page and clicks the pencil down.

MACK stands back in the dark by the door, 55, and writes one line in a pocket notebook.

INT. TRI-COUNTY AUCTION BARN - NIGHT (DAYS COMPRESSED)

The barn runs loud with grinders and the crew works late under the lamps.

DUTCH sits at the plywood table, 76, with two sets of drawings laid out in front of him.

On the table lies the federal completion sheet, stamped and squared at the corner.

In his binder, on the next page over, the same box shows a couch built in and a rack of cartridges, with four spares penciled per unit.

He closes the binder and sets the federal sheet square on top of it.

At a veterinary supply counter across the county, GUNNY sets two drums of white granules up by the register, 71, and counts out cash.

The clerk rings it up and looks at the drums.

CLERK:
Y'all got surgery coming up?

GUNNY:
Something like it.

Back at the shop Gunny runs a grease pencil across the plywood with Tito standing next to him.

GUNNY:
This lime here soaks up what you breathe back out. Fella asleep don't burn much, so one can runs him most of a day.

GUNNY:
You swap it every fifteen hours or so and keep a stack of 'em ready.

He points the pencil at the welding bottles standing along the wall.

GUNNY:
The oxygen we already buy by the bottle. It's on the invoices with the welding.

He marks the shelf edge off in ranks of four and numbers each rank.

A forklift sets a pallet of welding bottles inside the roll-up door and a driver hands Dutch an invoice.

Dutch signs it and lays it on the stack with the other slips.

TITO stands at the lathe turning a canister down to size, 24, the binder page clipped up in front of him.

He lifts a finished canister, taps it twice with two knuckles, and taps it twice again.

Across the floor JOSS feeds a couch cushion through the upholstery station, 26, and he keeps his mouth shut and works.

STITCH lays the last of the foam into a couch and presses it down until it holds the shape of a man's back, 74.

Along the frame rail the copper purge lines run down where no inspector will ever look.

CRICKET walks the row of open crates, 79, and looks in at the couches one at a time.

INT. TRI-COUNTY AUCTION BARN - NIGHT

A desk lamp burns over a plywood table. Mack Boone, 55, freight-and-salvage, sits alone with a freight booking sheet squared in front of him and a floor scale dragged up against his boot.

He lifts an archival box onto the scale. The board is empty, flaps hanging open.

The needle swings up and settles. He watches it, then pencils the number onto the sheet.

He sets the box off and lifts the next one. Same swing. Same heavy number.

Four numbers run down the sheet now, each circled hard enough to dent the paper.

He runs the pencil down the shipping weight printed on the manifest and holds it beside his own column. Each of his four numbers sits thirty kilos above the printed weight.

He circles the gap and sets the pencil down. He sits there a while.

He stands. He walks the dark shop floor past the welding bays and the crates stacked up into the rafters.

He stops at a low shape under a tarp by Bay Two. He takes a corner of the canvas and lifts it.

Under it sits a couch. Strapped down to the cushions, a packed form the size and shape of a MAN.

He looks at it a long moment. He lets the tarp fall and carries the sheet back to the table where the others sit in the lamp light.

MACK:
Nothing on this manifest breathes, gentlemen.

Earl "Cricket" Dawes, 79, sets his coffee down on the plywood and answers without getting up.

CRICKET:
Tuesday the truck carries six boxes out on your paper. Six of us are in them. The load reads right because that dummy already weighs what a man weighs. They wave it through the gate and nobody counts us at the yard.

Mack stays on his feet. He looks down at Cricket.

MACK:
You understand there's no backing out once you're up there. Bad heart at four g's, your age, no doctor closer than a quarter million miles.

Gunny Tibbs, 71, Navy retired, leans back against the bench and looks up at him. Not unkindly.

GUNNY:
Boone, I've buried better men than me for worse reasons than this. Sit down or go home. Either's fine. Quit standing there doing arithmetic on our behalf.

Joss Reed, 26, dock hand, watches from the dark past the last crate.

JOSS:
You're all insane. What do you need from me?

Tito Alvarez, 24, the welder, brings his knuckles twice against the crate wall.

Two knocks on plywood carry across the shop.

Nobody at the table says anything.

Mack pulls the bench out and sits down.

He reaches into his coat and takes out his pen.

INT. TRI-COUNTY AUCTION BARN - NIGHT (LATER)

The lamp still burns over the plywood table. Mack Boone, 55, freight-and-salvage, stands at the head of it with the crew around him and their coffee going cold.

MACK:
From tonight, everything changes how it moves. Nothing electronic. No phones, no email, no cloud. Nothing with a battery you didn't build yourself.

Joss Reed, 26, dock hand, sits back on a crate at the edge of the light.

JOSS:
Then how do two hundred guys and four states coordinate a--

Dutch Haas, 76, engineer, answers without looking up from the binder in his lap.

DUTCH:
Handwritten letters. The ham radio net, on a schedule, in code. A book cipher.

Dutch sets a swollen 1971 READER'S DIGEST on the plywood, the pages fat with damp.

JOSS:
That's insane. That's, that's Revolutionary War stuff.

Gunny Tibbs, 71, Navy retired, turns a coffee cup slow in his hands.

GUNNY:
They've got every algorithm ever written. We've got Valley Forge.

Morning light lies flat along a gravel road. A hand pushes an envelope into a rural mailbox and lifts the little red flag. The face of it reads TRI-COUNTY FEED COOPERATIVE, RE: PARTS.

Farther down the road a second flag goes up. A third stands already.

Inside the post office a mail carrier tosses one of the feed-cooperative envelopes into a sorting tray between two packs of grocery coupons.

Back in the barn under the same lamp, Tito Alvarez, 24, welder, raises a small film camera and shoots the finished couch twice.

The shutter clacks.

He winds the canister out and drops it into a Folgers can half full of them, then settles the can in the bottom of his toolbox.

In the Dawes kitchen, Cricket Dawes, 79, sits at the table with the same swollen Reader's Digest open under a lamp. Danny Dawes, 50, his son, reads off a folded sheet.

DANNY:
Fourteen. Two. Nine.

Cricket thumbs to page fourteen, runs a finger down the second column, counts nine words in, and writes one on a pad.

Danny turns the pad and looks at it.

DANNY:
That's a grocery list.

CRICKET:
This week it is.

Back at the shop table, Elmore "Stitch" McGrew, 74, the airplane man, tips his chair back on two legs. Mack goes around the table with a nod at each.

GUNNY:
My sister's. Down in Montgomery.

STITCH:
Airplane parts, Wichita. True enough.

DUTCH:
The archival-standards conference. Dayton.

A beat.

DUTCH:
There is one.

Mack looks to Danny.

DANNY:
Fishing.

INT. TRI-COUNTY AUCTION BARN - DAY

The barn is swept clean down the middle. Morning light drops through the high windows onto a long open lane of bare concrete.

DUTCH HAAS, 76, engineer, stands at a card table with a thick black binder open to a tabbed page. A stack of fresh carbon forms sits squared beside it.

He lifts the top form and turns it so the others can read the header. It reads FLIGHT CREW MEDICAL EXAMINATION, STANDARDS OF 1968.

DUTCH:
NASA wrote a physical in 1968. It is the last standard that ever mattered, and it is the one in this binder. We do all of it or none of it.

A hundred feet down the barn, an eye chart hangs off a nail in the far wall. Stitch stands on a strip of tape at the near end and reads down it.

STITCH:
Bottom line's got a print date on it. You want that too?

Dutch writes without raising his head.

DUTCH:
Line eleven. Nobody reads line eleven.

A wooden step box sits in the middle of the lane. STITCH McGREW, 74, steps up onto it and down, up and down, holding a slow count under his breath.

On the fourth step his knee cracks, loud enough to carry across the concrete. His count doesn't change. Nobody looks over.

Dutch flips back to a dog-eared page and runs a finger down the margin.

DUTCH:
There were waivers in '68 too. Compensating technique, documented.

Stitch steps off. CRICKET DAWES, 79, takes the box next and steps it the full two minutes, then stops with his hands loose at his sides.

JOSS REED, 26, kneels and puts two fingers on Cricket's wrist, his eyes on the smartwatch on his own arm.

JOSS:
Two minutes after all that stepping. Fifty-four. Sitting still he's down to fifty-one.

Joss glances at his own wrist, then back at Cricket.

JOSS:
Mine's higher than that right now, just kneeling here. Four hundred dollars, this thing.

Not one of the old men reacts. Dutch looks up at Cricket.

DUTCH:
Anything to note.

CRICKET:
There's a knothole in this bench. I'll have it plugged before you're done.

Cricket sits down on an overturned bucket, opens a pocketknife, and starts cutting a pine peg down to size.

Joss unbuckles the watch, carries it to the coffee can by the door, and lets it drop in.

A plywood crate stands open on the floor. Inside it a wind-up kitchen timer sits next to four twenty-dollar bills, held flat under a socket wrench.

GUNNY TIBBS, 71, Navy retired, climbs into the crate and folds himself down onto his back.

GUNNY:
Set it for the hour. Don't lift the lid early on my account.

TITO ALVAREZ, 24, welder, winds the timer, sets it in beside Gunny, and lowers the lid down over him.

The timer ticks inside the box. Nobody says anything.

Cricket works the peg into the knothole. It stands proud and won't seat. He pulls it and shaves it again.

The timer rings. Tito lifts the lid off.

Gunny sits up in no hurry and looks down at the money under the wrench.

GUNNY:
Whose twenty is on top?

Joss lifts a hand from the back.

JOSS:
Mine.

GUNNY:
It's mine now, son.

Dutch takes the four carbon forms off the table and files them into the rings one at a time.

DUTCH:
Same result as 1968. All four.

He thumbs the binder open again and adds a line at the bottom.

DUTCH:
Slower on the step box. All four of you. I wrote it down.

Cricket taps the peg flush into the knothole with the butt of the knife. It sits level with the bench.

STITCH:
Best year there ever was.

INT. TRI-COUNTY AUCTION BARN - NIGHT

Night in the barn, and MACK stands at the plywood table with a printed federal seizure inventory in front of him, 55.

The crew waits around the table while he runs a finger down the list.

MACK:
Before I trust that warehouse with y'all, I want to watch it lose something small.

He stops on the first line and turns the sheet so CRICKET can read it, 79.

MACK:
Item one. The trainer.

A week later a flatbed pulls up to the barn with VALLEY SALVAGE & SURPLUS painted on the door.

Every piece on the deck wears a fresh orange stencil that reads SCRAP LOT 44-C.

The DRIVER swings down with a clipboard and looks at his watch.

DRIVER:
Sign for lot 44-C. Scrap conveyance, buyer's copy. Somebody paid the freight to here, don't ask me who, I just drive. And I got a two o'clock in Ogallala.

On the buyer's copy a line reads SOLD TO the TRI-COUNTY FEED COOPERATIVE.

Cricket reads down the line items, HOMEBUILT TRAINER COMPONENTS, SOLD AS SCRAP, NON-FUNCTIONAL.

He looks at the gauges sitting whole and the panels turned up to the sky on the deck.

CRICKET:
Says non-functional.

DRIVER:
It does say that.

Cricket signs the buyer's copy and hands the clipboard back.

CRICKET:
Barn's where it was.

Inside, the men set the trainer down and bolt it through the same four holes in the floor.

One orange SCRAP stencil stays on the rail, and no one scrubs it off.

DUTCH throws the breakers in the order they always go, 76.

The amber light on the panel flickers and comes up steady.

Dutch keys the panel and picks the drill back up.

DUTCH:
Net's open. Tuesday.

STITCH settles onto a stool by the rack, 74.

STITCH:
There he is.

Dutch turns to Cricket at the panel.

DUTCH:
Bus B. What's it read.

Cricket taps the glass on the gauge with a knuckle.

CRICKET:
Twenty-eight point four. Better than it left.

GUNNY stands at the end of the panel, 71.

GUNNY:
Run your card, Commander.

Above the panel, taped where a mission patch would go, hangs the folded pink county seizure sheet.

Cricket puts his hand on the throttle.

CRICKET:
Guidance internal.

INT. FEDERAL SURPLUS HOLDING, OUTSIDE LINCOLN - DAY

Shelving runs back into the dark, rack after rack, each shelf stenciled with a number.

An orange sticker sits on every seized thing down the aisle, a flight trainer up on blocks, crates of tooling, a high-school football trophy with a town's name across the base.

Four racks stand off by themselves at the end, suits hung by the shoulders, brass museum tags wired to the wrists.

MACK BOONE, 55, comes down the aisle with the lot sheet in one hand, checking the numbers against the tags.

He waves the forklift driver over to the four racks.

MACK:
The four hundred took the whole lot, the tool crates and that old trophy and all of it, and the truck's gotta be back Thursday, so let's get 'em loaded before we lose the light.

The forks slide under a pallet of scrap and set it down on the flatbed.

The suits go up after that, laid flat between two pallets, the tags hanging off the wrists.

ON THE SHEET -- line nine reads DEGRADED TEXTILE ARTIFACTS, NON-FLIGHT-RATED, SOLD AS SCRAP.

At the gate a guard runs a finger down the sheet, glances at the pallets, and waves the flatbed out.

The flatbed backs into a metal hangar out on the East Texas flat, and the four suits come off onto a workbench under the lights.

ELMORE "STITCH" McGREW, 74, bends over that bench with a length of new hose in both hands.

STITCH:
These lines have all gone stiff on me, every one of 'em, fifty years old give or take, so there's no savin' any of it, I'm just cuttin' in all new.

He lays the old hose beside the new and marks it off with a pencil.

STITCH:
Seals are flat too. No book anywhere tells you the size on these, so I been cuttin' 'em by hand off the old ones.

Stitch brushes soapy water down a seam and works a hand pump until the suit swells.

Bubbles crawl up along the seam, a whole line of them.

STITCH:
Every place she bubbles, that's air gettin' out on us.

He seats a seal, brushes the seam again, and the bubbles thin down and quit.

STITCH:
And when they quit like that, she's holdin'.

He lays a fresh patch over one knee and rolls it flat with his thumb.

The brass tag stays wired to the wrist, and Stitch leaves it be, dabbing the soapy brush careful around it.

GUNNY TIBBS, 71, stands at the far end of the bench and lifts a pair of white gloves off the rack, one at a time, flat on both palms.

He sets each glove down beside its suit, the fingers straightened, palm turned up.

GUNNY:
These go on last. And nobody sets a coffee down on this bench while I've got 'em out.

Four suits stand on the racks along the far wall, filled out and upright, the brass tags turning slow on their wires.

INT. TRI-COUNTY AUCTION BARN - DAY

The federal drawings lie squared on the table with the corners lined up and nothing else beside them.

The couches are gone from the bay and the binder is nowhere on the floor.

One pallet sits against the back wall under a gray tarp, roped down at all four corners.

The door rolls up and ADMINISTRATOR J. PELL, 50s, steps in with his lanyard and a clipboard, a photographer a pace behind him.

MACK BOONE, 55, meets him at the table and turns the drawings so they face the right way for Pell.

PELL:
Oh, this is good. This is the thing I keep telling the office, you drive all the way out and it just runs itself, you barely have to touch it.

MACK:
Kept the table clear for you. That's the federal set, the drawings you mailed us.

Pell walks the floor slow, and TITO ALVAREZ, 24, lifts his welding hood at the far bay as he passes.

PELL:
That's clean work, son. Somebody teach you or you just pick it up?

TITO:
Little of both, I guess.

The photographer raises the camera and Pell steps back to the crate line and lays a hand on the nearest box.

PELL:
Get the crates in behind me. Heritage labor, that's the phrase they want upstairs, the old hands retiring the gear and preserving it themselves on the way out.

PELL:
Small crew for a Thursday.

MACK:
Dawes runs the co-op errands Thursdays, so it's just this handful today.

Pell stops at a row of valves plumbed into the ends of the boxes and taps one with his pen.

PELL:
Now what's a box want with plumbing.

DUTCH HAAS, 76, looks up from a fitting he's checking and keeps the wrench in his hand.

DUTCH:
The fabric sat fifty years. Forty-eight on the early lot. You pull the air out so it lays flat instead of cracking, then you put nitrogen back in so the color doesn't turn on you.

Pell writes in the visit log and reads it off as the pen moves.

PELL:
Exceeds requirement. They're going to love that in the report.

JOSS REED, 26, stands against the back wall a step off the tarped pallet with his hands in his jacket.

Pell comes down the wall and his pen knocks the tarp once without stopping.

PELL:
And this one.

JOSS:
Floor absorbent.

Pell nods and keeps walking toward the door.

Joss watches the back of the lanyard and does not move off the wall.

Pell signs the bottom of the log and hands Mack the yellow copy.

PELL:
Send me the crate count by Friday and we're closed out for the quarter.

MACK:
You'll have it Friday morning, count and the weights both.

The SUV pulls out through the gate and the dust drifts down over the lot.

Nobody in the shop moves for three full seconds.

Joss lets his breath go and turns his head to the tarp.

INT. SENATE HEARING ROOM - DAY

MIRA VESS, 40s, sits alone at the witness table, one closed folder squared in front of her, cameras clicking behind her.

THE CHAIRMAN, silver-haired and easy, tips forward into his microphone with a printed sheet in his hand.

CHAIRMAN:
Ms. Vess, I'll go straight to your founder. Mr. Hale hasn't exactly been shy about what he thinks of this program. Has he said any of that to you directly, inside the company.

Vess turns her water glass a quarter and leaves it.

VESS:
Frequently. In colorful terms. I can provide dates.

A low laugh moves down the gallery.

CHAIRMAN:
Then you'd grant me a man like that, with his hands still on the controls, is some kind of risk to a broadcast the whole country's going to be sitting down to watch.

VESS:
He is not built for quiet. He posts what he thinks. Usually before breakfast. You have his feed. Subpoena his drafts folder if you want the rest.

The laugh comes back and two of the senators go with it.

An aide leans in at the Chairman's shoulder and says something he waves off.

CHAIRMAN:
There's a proposal in this room to hand Frontier to a federal receiver until Unity Day. For stability, they tell me. I expect you've got a view on that.

VESS:
A receiver wouldn't know this company in six months. Your broadcast is in nine weeks. The Accord flies on schedule if the company stays in the hands that run it. Mine.

She sits back an inch and lets the room settle.

VESS:
Watch him as closely as you like. He's loud. His calendar's clean.

A phone lies faceup in a dark office, the hearing playing small and bright on the glass.

MAGNUS HALE sits behind it in the dark, his thumb resting over a half-typed post.

ON THE SCREEN -- the draft reads, My COO and the mother of my children just

His thumb stays over the last word.

He holds the backspace down until the line is gone.

He turns the phone face down on the desk.

PANELIST (RADIO):
— and when even Mira Vess won't defend him, what's left to defend?

Hale does not turn it back over.

INT. DAWES BARN - NIGHT

EARL "CRICKET" DAWES, 79, stands at the barn workbench with a canvas kit bag open and a handwritten list pinned under a wrench.

He reads a line off the list and sets a logbook down in the bag, then lays a slide rule alongside it.

DANNY DAWES, 50, stops in the barn doorway with one hand still on the frame.

DANNY:
I know what's in the barn, Dad. I've known about a year now. Figured you'd say something when it got to where it mattered.

Cricket doesn't stop. He sets a zippo on top of the logbook.

DANNY:
I'm not going to say any of the things. Your age, or the law, or Mom. You'd just stand there and let me get all the way through it.

CRICKET:
I would.

A folded photograph goes in next and he doesn't look at it.

Danny pushes off the door frame and turns to leave.

DANNY:
County's squared, by the way. Paid it Tuesday, so that's handled.

Cricket's hand stops flat on the bag.

CRICKET:
I'll pay you back.

DANNY:
I know.

Danny stops again with his hand on the frame.

DANNY:
You need a driver, or.

CRICKET:
Thursday. Four a.m. Dress like a farmer.

DANNY:
I am a farmer.

Later, in the bedroom off the barn, Cricket lifts the bag onto the quilt and keeps working down the list.

CRICKET:
You'll want the --

He stops with the word half out and the room stays quiet around him.

His thumb catches a raised seam inside the bag, old thread, three sides of small even stitches that aren't his.

He opens the stitches with the pocketknife.

Inside sits one dried orange ZINNIA, pressed flat and gone brittle.

He doesn't turn it over or hold it up to the bulb.

He folds the canvas back over the seam and packs the rest of the bag around it.

Across the country, in a kitchen in East Los Angeles, saints hang on the wall and a sewing machine sits dark by the window.

LITA ALVAREZ, 80s, takes one end of a folded flag at the table, and TITO ALVAREZ, 24, lifts the other.

They fold it in half down the long side, then down the long side again.

She starts the triangle at her end and he holds the tension while it comes across in tight, sharp turns.

The last corner tucks under and holds.

She works a small St. Christopher medal deep into the folds until it disappears.

She sets the triangle in his two hands.

Tito kisses her forehead and goes out.

Through the window, he lowers the triangle onto the truck seat with both hands.

Lita sits back down at the sewing machine and turns off the lamp.

INT. FRONTIER AEROSPACE, CARGO INTEGRATION HALL - DAY

Six crates ride the cradles down the center of the hall, the stencils painted black and huge on the flanks. The first four read LOT A, OLD IDEAS. LOT B, OLD CULTURE. LOT C, OLD CUSTOMS. LOT D, OLD HABITS.

Two more sit at the end of the row, LOT E and LOT F, both stenciled SUPPLEMENTARY CONTAINMENT.

ADMINISTRATOR J. PELL, fifties, gray suit, a heritage-compliance lanyard squared flat to his sternum, walks the head of the row with a clipboard and a wide, easy smile.

A photographer keeps a half-step behind him, camera up, working the light off the crate flanks.

PELL:
Get the whole row in the shot if you can. They like all six back at the office.

Pell taps his pen on the top corner of the clipboard and turns to face the floor.

PELL:
Random re-weigh. Compliance is a rhythm, folks. Random means random.

MACK BOONE, fifty-five, canvas jacket, a fold of invoices in his shirt pocket, stands off the first cradle with his hands loose at his sides.

At the console the SCALE TECH, forties, a coffee thermos sweating by his elbow, watches his gauge and says the number to nobody in particular.

SCALE TECH:
Lot A declares three-eighty. I've got four-eleven-two.

Pell keeps the smile and makes a small mark on the sheet.

PELL:
Little heavy. Run the next one.

SCALE TECH:
Lot B, declared three-eighty. Four-ten-eight.

SCALE TECH:
C, same declared. Four-twelve, near enough even.

SCALE TECH:
D. Four-eleven-nine.

Pell stops writing. He looks down the row of stencils and then back at the sheet.

PELL:
Thirty kilos over, times four crates. That's a hundred and twenty kilos of something, Mr. Boone.

Mack shifts his weight and looks at the console, not at Pell.

MACK:
Could be the couch upgrade. Archival spec revision come through in March --

PELL:
Re-run it. Cell check first.

The hall goes quiet. The air handlers hum somewhere up in the roof.

The scale tech reaches under the console lip and raps the number-three load cell twice with his knuckles.

SCALE TECH:
Four-eleven-nine. Four-oh-eight-two. Four-thirteen-five.

He looks at the crate. He looks at the gauge. He looks down at his own clipboard and holds there.

Up in the crane cab JOSS REED, twenty-six, dock coveralls, both hands lifted off the levers, sits without moving.

The tech uncaps his pen. He writes slow and says it plain as it goes down.

SCALE TECH:
Calibration drift, cell three. All four reads invalidated. Corrected tare applied. Reads within tolerance after correction.

He puts his initials on the line, tears the carbon copy loose, and holds it up over his shoulder.

Mack steps in and takes the copy. The tech is already turned back to his console, thumbing the lid off the thermos, his back to the room.

In the cab Joss lowers his hands to the levers, one finger at a time.

Pell takes the sheet from Mack and reads it. He reads it again. He lays it on the clipboard and runs his thumb along the edge until it sits square to the corner.

PELL:
Hm.

He walks the row once, unhurried, and stops at the LOT D cradle.

PELL:
All right. Let's get the tag.

Pell clicks the pen and signs the inspection tag hanging on the LOT D cradle, then fits it back into the little holder for the camera.

PELL:
Good. That's a clean one, folks. Appreciate you being patient with the re-weigh.

The camera finds the tag square in its holder, the word inspected stamped across the top and Pell's signature filling the line below it.

The shutter clicks.

EXT. FRONTIER AEROSPACE, MAIN GATE - PRE-DAWN

DANNY DAWES, fifty, feed cap low, both hands riding high on the wheel, rolls a farm truck up to the Frontier main gate with the headlights turned down.

GUNNY TIBBS, seventy-one, gray coveralls, a ballcap squared dead level, sits shotgun with a laminated work order flat on his knee.

The order reads VALLEY SALVAGE AND SURPLUS, ARCHIVAL UNIT FINAL SERVICING, BAY 1. Four names run down the side of it.

A gate guard, maybe twenty, leans out of the booth and walks a flashlight across the cab.

GUARD:
Y'all know where you're going?

Gunny hands the order across and holds the kid's eyes without any hurry in it.

GUNNY:
Son, we were servicing this bay before your daddy made the varsity.

The guard clicks the light off and waves the truck on through.

Danny keeps his knuckles white on the wheel and his eyes straight ahead, and he drives.

The truck pulls into Bay 1 and stops under the work lights.

Six crates sit open on their cradles, a molded couch inside each one. A purge cart hums along the row.

One at a time the old men come off the cart and lower themselves down into the couches. Nobody rushes any of it.

Joss's dock crew crosses the floor on their own errands and never slows for the row.

CRICKET DAWES, seventy-nine, gray coveralls, settles into the LOT A couch with a canvas kit bag held between his knees.

JOSS REED, twenty-six, a dock badge clipped to his collar, crouches at the open panel with a torque gun leaned against his leg.

CRICKET:
Tuesday net's at nineteen hundred. Your frequency card's taped under the console. Don't improvise.

JOSS:
Copy. No improvising.

CRICKET:
And Joss. Thank your dad for the radio.

Joss keeps a hand on the panel and doesn't seat it yet.

JOSS:
Fly good, old man.

He fits the panel down and runs the torque gun along the bolts, eight of them, one and then the next.

The purge valve hisses and takes hold.

MACK BOONE, fifty-five, a clipboard under one arm, walks the sealed row and raps the flank of LOT B twice with two knuckles.

Two knocks come back from inside it. He works down to C, then D, then A, and every one answers him two for two.

TITO ALVAREZ, twenty-four, a welder's scarred hands, kneels at LOT E and settles a folded canvas triangle into a padded corner mount.

He presses it home and checks it with two knuckles, once, and then again.

A dockworker, fifties, twenty years of lanyard tape wound thick on his badge clip, comes down the row with a clipboard and stops at LOT D.

An amber flag stands up on the LOT D latch. The book says he opens it.

He lifts the panel.

Inside, an old man lies packed into the couch, a kit bag between his knees, his eyes open and looking straight up at him.

The dockworker holds still. A second passes.

Another passes.

A third passes.

He looks down at his clipboard. He looks at the inspection tag on the latch, stamped inspected and signed already in Pell's hand.

The old man does not blink.

The dockworker pushes the amber flag back down and seats the panel over the man.

He prints two words across the log in block capitals, ALL CLEAR, and walks on to LOT E without looking back.

A transporter noses under the row and takes all six crates up together.

The high door rolls open and the stack moves out into the first gray light, the stencils on the flanks catching it as they go.

Mack stops at the gate log and signs the contractor crew out, four names, working down them with the one pen.

Joss comes up beside him, pulling the badge off his collar.

JOSS:
Net's quiet. Two clicks if it stays that way.

MACK:
Go home. Sleep.

EXT. FRONTIER LAUNCH COMPLEX, PAD 1 - NIGHT

The rocket stands white in the floodlight against the black.

Vapor rolls down the hull and spreads out across the cold concrete.

No mark rides the side of it. The skin is white from the nose to the base.

The floods hold the pad. The steam keeps coming off the metal.

Inside the gala hall the tables run in long rows under warm light.

A scale model of the rocket sits under glass at the center of the room. A small brass plate on the base reads HARMONY BANNER.

PRESIDENT ZORAN MARWANI, 41, works the tables with a glass in one hand and a hand for every shoulder he passes.

He stops at a table near the front and crouches down to a seated guest.

MARWANI:
There you are. No, don't get up, please, you came all this way for us.

MARWANI:
How's the boy. He still building the little ones out of the soup cans.

He laughs at the answer and pats the man twice on the arm and stands.

A wide barn-door screen fills the wall behind the riser with the pad and the standing rocket.

He steps up onto the low riser and taps the side of his glass with his ring.

MARWANI:
Thank you. Everybody, sit down, please. I'll keep it short. I always say that and I never do it, so.

MARWANI:
Tonight a rocket rises with no flag on its side. Think of that. Not conquest. Not pride. Repair.

Inside mission control the screens light the faces along the consoles.

MIRA VESS, 40s, stands at the back glass with her arms crossed and her eyes on the count clock.

ADMINISTRATOR J. PELL, 50s, stands a few feet down the same glass with a folder held flat to his chest.

A flight director leans to his mic at the front console.

FLIGHT DIRECTOR:
All stations, we're inside two minutes. Give me a go or a no-go for the launch.

CONTROLLER (RADIO):
Fuel's good here, we're go.

CONTROLLER (RADIO):
Guidance is go.

CONTROLLER (RADIO):
Range is go, you're clear.

Vess does not move. Her eyes stay on the clock.

Pell opens the folder, runs a finger down one line, and closes it again.

Inside the sealed crate the padded walls press in close around a man on his back.

EARL 'CRICKET' DAWES, 79, lies back with a checklist card clipped to the front of his suit.

A low hum runs up through the walls of the crate.

The hum climbs. Dust ticks off the seam of the lid in the amber light.

CRICKET:
Straps tight. Card's set.

CRICKET:
Hum's up. Right on the minute.

Back at the pad the rocket still stands white in the floods.

FIRE pours out from under the rocket and the night goes orange for a mile.

The roar reaches the gala hall a second late and rattles the glasses on the tables.

The rocket lifts off the pad and climbs up into the dark.

ON THE GROUND CAMERAS --

The white skin of the booster begins to peel back on the climb. It comes off in burning sheets along the length of it.

Color shows through where the white is gone. Red and white and blue rise up through the scorch.

ON THE GALA SCREEN --

The color climbs across the big screen above the room.

The raised glasses hang in the air and nobody drinks.

Marwani keeps the smile and holds his glass up to a room that has turned away from him to the screen.

Inside Roy's Diner the late crowd fills the counter under the TV.

BUCK, 70s, sits at the counter in a feed cap with his eyes up on the TV over the pie case.

BUCK:
There she goes in a minute. Ours. Whatever's riding her.

On the diner TV the color breaks up through the white.

The whole counter comes off its stools at once. Nobody says a word.

WITH CRICKET --

The weight takes him down deep into the molding of the crate. He lays his hand flat on the underside of the lid and holds it there.

The amber light dims down under the load. It holds low, and then it comes back up.

ON THE SCREEN --

The lower piece of the stack falls away from the top. The upper part lights and pulls ahead of it.

At the diner counter the men watch the lower piece drop off. One by one they sit back down.

Back at the pad in the gray light the booster stands down on its legs again.

Steam rises off the scorched red and white and blue of its skin.

The ground crew stand at the base with their heads tipped back, looking up at it. No one covers it. No one speaks.

The crew holds there and keeps looking up. The steam keeps rising off the metal.

Far above, inside the crate bay, the four boxes ride in their straps in the dark.

The engine cuts and the sound stops all at once.

The kit bag floats up off Cricket's chest to the end of its lanyard and hangs there.

The bay is dark. Four sealed crates ride in their straps.

Two KNOCKS come from inside one crate.

A pause. Two knocks answer back from the crate across the bay.

Four amber lights burn low in four sealed boxes.

Outside the one small window the Earth turns gold.

INT. HARMONY ONE, CARGO BAY - SHIP'S NIGHT

A panel swings inward on crate C, and GUNNY TIBBS, 71, folds out into the dark in thermal underwear and gray wool socks, a penlight hooded in his fist.

He hands himself along the crates, works a spent canister loose from a service port and seats a fresh one.

At crate D he threads a steel thermos through the port, and it slides out of sight inside.

CRICKET (WHISPER):
Obliged.

The bay door seal hisses.

Gunny goes flat behind crate F, his socks drifting up loose behind him, the penlight dead in his hand.

LINDQVIST pushes in on a handhold and walks a flashlight down the painted crate numbers.

The beam crosses crate F and keeps going.

LINDQVIST:
It's freezing down here. Nobody bothers heating the cargo end.

A vent hatch hangs half open by Gunny's shoulder. He pushes it flush with one finger.

Lindqvist pulls himself back through the hatch, and the light leaves with him.

Gunny comes off the crate and pushes to the window, both hands on the frame.

The Moon fills a third of the glass. He holds there and looks at it a long time ...

He folds back into crate C and draws the panel shut.

Four amber lights hold in the dark.

A run of knuckle taps travels crate to crate, slow and patterned.

Inside crate A, a penlight clicks on over a spiral notebook, and Dutch pencils one letter, waits, pencils the next.

ON THE PAGE -- the pencil has spelled out, ANYONE ELSE'S HOTEL GOT ROOM SERVICE.

Dutch raps back on the crate wall with the pencil butt, slow and even.

ON THE PAGE -- under it, in his own hand, TOLD HIM. TAKE IT UP WITH THE SPEC AUTHOR.

A cone of worklight crosses the bay, and OBSERVER SHEN drifts in behind it, reading serials off the crate faces into a tablet.

He taps the stylus to each tag as he passes it.

He stops at crate D. His head tilts a few degrees.

He drifts in close and reads the inspection tag, which an inspector named Pell has signed and marked as cleared.

The gauge beside it reads nominal.

He works the glove off his right hand and wedges it under his arm.

He lays his bare palm flat against the crate skin.

The palm holds there. Five seconds go by, then eight.

WITH CRICKET -- inside crate D he lies dead still and holds a breath all the way in.

Brandt, the commander of the Harmony crew, leans in from the corridor with one hand on the frame.

BRANDT:
Shen. Burn prep's on. Strap in, twenty minutes.

The palm lifts. Shen works the glove back on.

The stylus moves. LOT D. SEALS INTACT. PURGE NOMINAL. NO ANOMALY.

Shen pushes off after Brandt, and the worklight goes with him.

The bay lights bank down to standby.

From crate C, two soft knocks.

Inside crate D, Cricket taps back twice against the wall.

EXT. DAWES FARM, PORCH - DAY

A washed black SUV sits in the farm lane with the engine still running.

DANNY DAWES, 50, stands just inside the screen door with one hand on the frame.

An AIDE in a pressed suit waits on the bottom step and holds a phone up flat on his palm.

On the phone, PRESIDENT ZORAN MARWANI, 41, smiles up at the door.

MARWANI:
I won't take your whole morning. I wanted to bring this one myself. We're amending the record. Apollo Eighteen goes back in the rolls, your father's name on the crew, where it should have been the whole time.

A breeze moves the wash hanging on the line at the side of the house.

MARWANI:
Flown status, by my own order. The wings. The whole history, put right.

MARWANI:
One small thing back. On the Fourth he stays home, sits out on his porch, lets the day go by where folks can see him. That's all of it. A good man at peace with all of us.

DANNY:
He's out.

Marwani keeps the smile and tips his head a little.

MARWANI:
Of course. When he's back, would you tell him the President drove all this way to ask him himself?

DANNY:
I'll pass it along if he calls.

MARWANI:
Mr. Dawes --

DANNY:
You have a good day now.

The screen door claps shut.

The aide stands on the step with the phone still held out to the empty doorway.

That night out on Ridge Road, a pickup sits pulled off in the grass with its lights out.

JOSS REED, 26, sits on the tailgate with a telegraph key and a radio, a red flashlight held in his teeth.

Danny hands him a folded sheet and Joss flattens it on his knee.

Joss works the key in short even taps and watches the sky.

The ship crosses overhead for six minutes and no more.

Two hundred miles up, inside crate D, the message pad fills a line at a time.

The lines come up one at a time, RECORD AMENDED, then FLOWN STATUS, then EXEC ORDER.

Then the condition, HOME ON PORCH UNITY DAY, and under it the one word VISIBLE.

CRICKET DAWES, 79, holds on that last word a moment in the amber light.

He knocks twice, and twice again, around the bay.

He sets his hand to the key by his knee and sends short and even.

Back on the tailgate the radio ticks and Joss reads it off the key.

JOSS:
Tell him, you can't give back what you never had.

The key keeps ticking and Joss keeps his eyes on it.

JOSS:
There's more.

JOSS:
Dawes out.

Overhead one point of light moves across the dark, west to east, steady.

Danny and Joss watch it all the way down to the horizon.

INT. FRONTIER MISSION CONTROL - NIGHT

The main screen throws a pale track across a dark room of consoles, and MIRA VESS, 40s, stands at the back rail with both hands on it.

A few feet off, ADMINISTRATOR PELL, 50s, runs a highlighter down a checklist on a clipboard, his lanyard swinging.

The flight director stands at the front console in a headset and quiets the room with one hand.

FLIGHT:
All right. Let's poll it. I want a go or no-go for the burn.

One after another the consoles call back that they are go.

FLIGHT:
Harmony One, you are go for trans-lunar injection.

Far above, inside the cargo bay of Harmony One, the lights are down.

Four crates sit strapped in rows in the dark. Amber lights glow on their faces.

A low push comes up through the floor and builds. The straps pull tight and the crate frames creak.

The engine catches and settles into a long roar.

Inside crate A, DUTCH, 76, holds a penlight in his teeth and runs a pencil down the margin of a binder.

He pencils a figure, checks it against the clock, and boxes the last line twice.

ON THE PAGE -- BURN NOMINAL. COAST 62 HRS. NO ABORT FROM HERE.

He keeps the penlight on the boxed line a moment, then clicks it off.

Back down in mission control, the room holds on the main screen.

On the main screen the track bends away from Earth and keeps going, out past the ring of the orbit and clear of it.

The flight director pulls the headset down around his neck.

FLIGHT:
Sixty-two hours to lunar orbit, gentlemen. Get some sleep.

Vess takes her hands off the rail, one finger at a time, and lets it go.

Pell caps his highlighter and clips it to the board.

PELL:
Well. Nothing stopping it now.

Vess doesn't answer him. She keeps her eyes on the screen.

Up in the ship again, the cargo bay sits quiet in the coasting dark.

Inside crate A, Dutch raps the wall twice, waits, then raps twice more.

From crate D two knocks come back, then two from crate B, then two from crate C.

WITH CRICKET -- inside crate D, CRICKET, 79, lies in the straps with his hands folded on his chest.

In crate B, STITCH, 74, lies with his eyes shut.

STITCH:
We've had the mic the whole trip, you know. You don't have to keep tapping at me.

CRICKET:
Yeah. Old habit. Fifty years of it, it's hard to shake.

Cricket picks at the strap across his chest with one finger.

CRICKET:
Can I ask you something about Sky King.

STITCH:
Go ahead.

CRICKET:
Did he ever get to fly it again?

Stitch takes a second. His voice comes back easy, a smile in it.

STITCH:
He flew it. The rest of his life.

One corner of Cricket's mouth pulls up. He works his thumb slow along one knuckle.

END OF ACT TWO.

INT. FRONTIER MISSION CONTROL - DAY

On the flight deck of Harmony One, the ESA commander Brandt keeps both gloved hands flat on the descent panel and reads the crosshair down toward the center of the screen. He is gray and careful at fifty, a year from his last flight.

Lindqvist works the throttle at the second seat, and behind them Observer Shen, the Bloc's man on the crew, stands at the hatch with his hands folded and watches the board instead of the window.

A green light trips on the panel under Brandt's thumb.

BRANDT:
Contact light. Engine stop.

The engine quits and the lander drops the last of the height and hits the surface.

Down in the cargo bay, four old men ride the slam out strapped along the wall in worn white suits.

The rack slams down against its stops and the straps snap taut out of order.

In Crate B a tarped case tears loose, slides half a foot along the deck, and stops hard against the man folded into the far corner.

On the cargo door a hinge takes the blow and sets a hair out of true.

Outside on the Sea of Tranquility, the dust the landing kicked up hangs a moment and then settles, and across every screen in America the picture goes clean.

HARMONY ONE stands on the gray flat, white in the sun, no flag on her flank.

Back on the flight deck, Lindqvist lets out a breath and reaches up to safe the switches over his head.

LINDQVIST:
Well. That's us down, then.

Shen has not moved from the hatch, and he watches the little broadcast light hold steady on the panel.

SHEN:
Both networks have you.

Brandt takes his hands off the panel and flexes them once.

Down in the bay, Cricket, Earl Dawes of Nebraska, 79 and a widower a year, thumbs the mic on his cuff and counts the men down the wall.

CRICKET:
Sound off.

Dutch lifts two fingers off his strap, a service binder clipped at his thigh.

DUTCH:
Here.

Gunny is already working his harness buckle and keys the mic without looking up.

GUNNY:
Tibbs, up.

The net goes quiet, and nothing comes back from the far corner of the bay.

CRICKET:
Stitch.

Still nothing off the far corner.

CRICKET:
Elmore.

A wet, ugly cough comes over the net.

Stitch is folded down over his own side against the far straps, and it takes him two tries to key the mic.

STITCH:
…M'fine. Caught the rack with my side is all.

GUNNY:
Don't you go quiet on this net again, Colonel.

CRICKET:
Copy.

Cricket makes a mark on the cuff card and moves his thumb to the next line.

Outside behind the lander, a camera boom swings out from its high shoulder and pans slow across the site for the people back home.

The boom sweeps the near landing leg, drifts on across the black sky, and never once turns to look behind the lander.

In the lander's shadow, four crates stand open on the deck.

Four suited figures pass tarped bundles and latched cases down the line and lash them onto the backup rover, the museum tags turning on their wrist cuffs.

The last man climbs aboard, reaches down, and raps the fender twice and twice again.

THE BACKUP ROVER rolls out of the shadow into the sun, its tracks laying fresh line across ground no boot has crossed in fifty years.

The dust the rover throws comes down all at once, in one place, too neat for the ground it fell on.

Out at the solar array, Brandt straightens up from the half-unfolded panels and turns north out of long habit.

A thin haze stands low over the flat to the north, out where nothing on the site should be moving.

He holds on it, three seconds, maybe four.

Lindqvist calls up from below the array, out of frame.

LINDQVIST:
Commander, panel four's ready for your sign-off.

Brandt turns back to the array and crouches down to the panel.

BRANDT:
Base station nominal. Harmony One, beginning retrieval operations at first light tomorrow, per the program.

EXT. SURVEYOR CRATER, APOLLO 12 SITE - LUNAR DAY

The Apollo 12 descent stage stands alone on the gray, its foil skin still bright gold in the sun, the experiment packages set out around it in a row where the crew left them.

Lindqvist stands at the edge of the old scuffed ground with a cue card up in his glove, reading it out slow for the cameras trailing him.

LINDQVIST:
We arrive as guests of history, to relieve it of its oldest burden—

He stops. The card stays up in front of his visor.

Where the first flag should stand, there is only a SOCKET HOLE punched down into the dust.

Fresh bootprints cross the old faded ones, and they are not the crew's.

Wheel tracks run in from the northwest and back out the same way.

Brandt, the commander, comes up beside him and keys the loop.

BRANDT (RADIO):
Harmony, Site One. The artifact is... not present.

ON A STREAM --

A man in his thirties fills a gaming chair under a ring light, veins standing in his neck, a wall of pinned clippings and diagrams behind him.

STREAMER:
There were NEVER any flags! Fifty years of soundstage and they're up there right now hunting for PROPS! Look at them! WAKE UP!

The chat column blurs upward and the donation chime keeps going and does not stop.

The tour reaches Fra Mauro, and the site gives them the same thing. A gold descent stage stands over a row of tools, and another hole waits in the dust where the flag stood.

Lindqvist stands over this one with the cue card held down at his side, not reading it.

LINDQVIST:
You can shut the cameras off. There's nothing to film here either.

Down at Roy's Diner, a television over the counter runs the Moon feed with the sound off. Buck, seventies, in a feed cap, sits on his stool with a coffee going cold in front of him. Earlene works the pot behind the counter.

BUCK:
Somebody took 'em.

Earlene tops off the cup without looking up at the set.

EARLENE:
Took 'em where, Buck? It's the Moon.

Buck keeps his eyes on the screen. A smile starts at one corner of his mouth and comes on slow.

Inside the Unity Day pavilion, banners hang over the stage, and Marwani, the program's master of ceremonies in a good suit, keeps his remarks rolling to a front row of schoolchildren.

MARWANI:
...and in just a few minutes now, these young people are going to watch us bring the very first flag back home.

Behind him the giant screen drops the Moon feed and holds on a single card. PLEASE STAND BY: UNITY DAY.

An aide slips in at his shoulder and says something low in his ear. Marwani keeps smiling down at the children.

MARWANI:
They tell me we'll have the picture back for you very shortly.

Back on the Moon at the first hole, Shen, the Bloc's observer, crouches over the ground near Brandt and switches to the private channel between them.

SHEN:
Commander. The possibility must be raised. If the artifacts were never — if the landings themselves were—

BRANDT:
Don't.

Neither of them says anything for a while.

Shen looks down at fifty years of undisturbed prints ringing the socket, and the new ones laid across them, still crisp at the edges.

Brandt straightens and turns his visor to the wheel tracks running off to the northwest, straight and even, all the way to the horizon.

BRANDT:
Whoever they are, they're not hiding their driving.

EXT. APPROACH TO TRANQUILITY BASE - LUNAR DAY

Three pressure suits work up a long grade of gray lunar dust, slow, bouncing a little, their shadows thrown far out ahead of them.

BRANDT:
Control, Harmony. We're at the bottom of the last rise. Can't see over it yet, give us a minute here.

Brandt's glove finds a rock and steadies him. The camera clipped to his chest points up the slope at nothing but ground and black sky.

LINDQVIST:
Bet you it's more rocks. That's about all this whole box has been so far.

BRANDT:
Could be.

The three of them climb the last of it together, Shen a step back off Lindqvist's shoulder.

The chest camera crests the top of the rise a half-step before the helmet does.

The front wall of the mission control room fills with COLOR.

A young controller comes up out of his chair so fast his headset cord snaps taut behind him.

Two rows of people stop what they are doing and look up at the same time.

A supervisor stands at the back with a phone halfway to his ear and forgets to finish lifting it.

Back on the lunar rise, six flags stand against the black. Five of them make a wide ring, and the first flag is up again in the center on its old pole.

Four aluminum lawn chairs sit in the dust. A squat grill stands next to a card table with a cooler beside it.

Four old men wait in the middle of all of it, in suits fifty years old. Three of them sit. One stands at the grill.

Behind them four crates stand on end, emptied, their stenciled faces turned to the camera. They read OLD IDEAS, OLD CULTURE, OLD CUSTOMS, OLD HABITS.

A hand-sewn flag hangs off a workshop pole by the grill. It carries fifty-one stars.

A camera on a tripod sits off to the side with its red light already on.

Brandt stops at the top of the rise. Lindqvist comes up level with him and Shen stays a pace back.

LINDQVIST:
Anders. Those are lawn chairs.

BRANDT:
Control, Harmony. We have the site. There's... give me a second here.

SHEN:
Do not touch anything.

BRANDT:
Nobody touches anything. Control, you getting this down there, or is it just us.

Inside Roy's Diner the TV plays up in the corner over the pie case.

EARLENE, sixties, works the counter with the coffee pot in her fist. She stops pouring a cup about halfway down.

BUCK, seventies, feed cap, sits on his stool and does not take his eyes off the screen in the corner.

EARLENE:
Where's Earl and them at? They're missing the damnedest thing that ever happened.

BUCK:
There they are.

The diner goes quiet for one beat. Then the whole counter comes up off its stools at once.

Across town the Unity Day pavilion is packed under its banners and its big screen.

MARWANI, fifties, a folded speech in one hand, stands at a lectern in the middle of a sentence.

The crowd in front of him quits looking at him. Every face lifts to something over his shoulder.

Marwani turns around. Behind him the ring of flags stands forty feet tall on the big screen.

In the front row the schoolchildren see flags and lawn chairs and a cookout on the Moon. They CHEER.

The cheering rolls back through the whole pavilion.

On a news set a panelist sits at her desk with the feed running on the monitor in front of her.

She presses a finger to her earpiece and keeps her eyes on the screen.

PANELIST:
— I'm being told those suits are the museum pieces. From the gift program. They're wearing the gifts.

In a Frontier training room a watch party crowds the tables, paper plates and a sheet cake, the feed up on the pull-down screen.

The MODULE 7 FACILITATOR, forties, stands at the back with a paper plate in her hand. Her eyes go across the four crate lids on the screen, left to right, and her mouth moves along with them.

The plate tips in her hand and a cookie slides off it onto the carpet. She does not look down.

At a Warsaw tram stop strangers stand packed shoulder to shoulder around one phone somebody holds up over the crowd.

The flags sit in their ring on the little screen. One man starts to clap, and in a few seconds the whole tram stop is clapping.

In a room lit by a ring light the STREAMER, thirties, veins standing out in his neck, rants straight into his camera. The feed of the flags plays in the corner of his monitor.

He stops. His jaw works and nothing comes.

The chat column on his second monitor scrolls by too fast to read any of it.

STREAMER:
Those flags are NEW, people. Look at the COLORS. They SWAPPED them—

Back at the grill on the Moon, GUNNY TIBBS, seventy-one, Navy retired, works a long spatula under whatever is on the grate.

He looks up the rise and sees the three Harmony suits standing there at the top of it.

Gunny brings the spatula up. He raises it slow, all the way up, and holds it there.

Hold on him.

EXT. TRANQUILITY BASE - LUNAR DAY

Brandt stands at the top of the rise, Lindqvist on his shoulder and Shen a pace back, the three Harmony suits looking down into the camp.

Off to the side the tripod camera holds its red light on all of it.

Brandt keys his loop and turns his shoulder toward the camp.

BRANDT:
Switching to channel two. Let's talk this over privately, gentlemen.

Down in the dust CRICKET, Earl Dawes, seventy-nine, works a wired handset in the glove of an Apollo suit gone yellow. He presses the transmit key on the open channel.

CRICKET:
We'll talk right here. Whole world's listening anyway.

Brandt comes back around to face them and keys the open loop, slow, for the record.

BRANDT:
All right. On the record, then. Who are you, and who sent you up here.

Cricket sets a hand on the chair arm and comes up out of it to his full height.

CRICKET:
We're the backup crew. NASA never processed us out. We're still on the roster, son. This is our mission.

Lindqvist takes a step down the slope before he catches himself.

LINDQVIST:
Where did you even COME from?

STITCH, Elmore McGrew, seventy-four, sits with one hand flat against his side. He answers without turning his head.

STITCH:
We came in the mail.

Stitch puts his weight on the chair arm, gets partway up, and lets himself back down into the chair.

He looks up the rise at the three of them.

STITCH:
This here's our camp. Pack the fuck off.

In the White House counsel's office four lawyers sit around a speakerphone on a long table, the feed muted on a wall screen behind them.

LAWYER #1, senior, jacket off, sleeves pushed back, keeps both hands flat on the table.

LAWYER #1:
I just want the one piece of paper that takes them off the Moon. Somebody go find me that.

LAWYER #2, the one who read the file, slides a printout across the table to him.

LAWYER #2:
It's been signed off every quarter since 1972, by career staff, under four statutes. He's not a trespasser. As far as the United States government is concerned, that man is federal personnel standing on his duty station.

ON THE SCREEN -- a personnel record reads DAWES, E., ASTRONAUT (ACTIVE), and under it a column of $0.00 entries running back fifty years.

LAWYER #1:
Then send somebody up there and remove them.

LAWYER #2:
Who? The only Americans on the Moon are the ones you want removed.

Nobody around the speakerphone says anything for a moment.

Lawyer #2 turns the page over and finds the next one.

LAWYER #2:
And sir, the President offered him the wings on a recorded line Tuesday. We can't call him a fraud without calling the President one.

Back on the rise, Shen, the observer who stayed quiet the whole way down, steps off the lip and starts toward the nearest flag.

The seated men come up out of their chairs, all but Stitch.

They move in between Shen and the flags, and not one of them says anything.

GUNNY, Tibbs, seventy-one, the tallest of them, steps to the front of them with a long grill spatula in one glove and looks down at Shen through the visor glass.

He holds there a long moment.

Gunny raises the spatula and points it once, back up the rise at the Harmony rover.

The loop stays quiet. Nobody moves.

Shen looks at the flags, then at the men, and steps back up onto the lip.

One at a time the old men lower themselves back into their chairs.

Gunny turns back to the grill and flips what's on it.

Brandt keys the loop.

BRANDT:
Harmony copies. Control, Harmony requests instructions.

EXT. TRANQUILITY BASE - LUNAR DAY

A voice comes onto the open loop from Earth, thinned by the distance, calm and official.

GENEVA (RADIO):
Harmony One, this is Accord Coordination, Geneva. You are directed to proceed with retrieval of all six artifacts. Immediately, please.

Brandt, the ESA commander, plants his boots on the gray flat and reaches for the flag staff standing in its old base.

Four old men in worn white suits cross into the gap between his glove and the staff and set their shoulders together, visors level, Cricket at the center of the line.

His glove stops a foot short of the staff and holds there.

Gunny, at the end of the line, reaches up and keys the open loop, slow and even, and every living room on Earth is on the channel.

GUNNY:
You want 'em? Come through us.

Brandt lowers his arm and takes one step back off the line.

BRANDT:
Geneva, Harmony One. The site is… occupied by personnel asserting jurisdiction. Requesting political guidance.

In Houston, the flight director stands over his console, gray and in his sixties, with Washington still talking in his headset.

A young controller holds a slip of paper up to his face with one word printed across it in block letters, ACKNOWLEDGE.

The flight director reads the slip, and instead of keying it up to the crew, he lifts the headset off both ears and lays it on the desk.

On the Moon, the loop stays open and empty, and nothing comes back but static.

Gunny unfolds a card table on the flat and deals four hands across it, one card at a time, and nobody reaches for a card.

The static breaks, and President Marwani comes onto the loop himself, forty-one and warm and unhurried, patched straight through from Earth to every set on the planet.

MARWANI (RADIO):
Friends. I've been listening the whole time, and I hear you, I really do. But this day belongs to everybody down here, and I would like to hand it back to them whole. As your Commander in Chief, I am ordering you to stand down.

Static holds for a moment.

Cricket reaches up without hurrying and keys his mic.

CRICKET:
You're not my commander, sir. NASA's civilian. Always was. That was the whole point of it.

The loop goes silent, all the way back to Geneva.

Shen steps up to Brandt's shoulder and speaks low, off the loop.

SHEN (WHISPER):
You did not touch the flag.

In Roy's Diner in Nebraska, Buck sits under the mounted television in his feed cap, seventies, a cup of coffee going cold in front of him.

His fist comes down on the counter hard enough to jump the spoon in the cup.

BUCK:
U-S-A!

The men down the counter pick it up, and the cups rattle in their saucers.

At the county fair, the restored carousel keeps turning while every grown-up climbs off the benches and shouts it at a phone.

On a highway overpass, a bedsheet flag hangs over the rail and a hundred cars lean on their horns at once.

In a Brooklyn loft, a rack of UNITY DAY shirts hangs by the door, and half the people wearing them catch themselves chanting, and some of them do not stop.

INT. FRONTIER AEROSPACE, HALE'S OFFICE - DAY

MAGNUS HALE, the man who built Frontier's rockets, sits alone in a dark office with the wall screen the only light on his face.

On the screen the helmet-cam clears the rise, and the ring of flags fills the wall.

Hale comes up out of the chair, slow.

He lets out one bark of a laugh.

Then he laughs for real, both hands going up on his head, and he walks a full circle around the dark office.

He stops with his hands still on his head and his shoulders going.

In the Frontier press room, Hale steps up to a crowded podium with a printed page in his hand.

He folds the page in half, folds it in half again, and sets it down squared to the edge of the podium.

HALE:
I can't read this one.

He looks straight into the cameras.

HALE:
Somebody used my rocket to do the finest thing an American's done in fifty years. You want somebody to punish for that? You want to nationalize me? Go. Fuck. Yourself.

He walks off the side of the stage and passes a reporter without turning his head.

HALE:
Tell the commie he can eat shit.

Behind him the room breaks open with camera flashes, and the aides wave at the booth to cut the feed.

The feed stays up, because the feed is his.

In the wings VESS, the woman who runs Frontier day to day, stands against the wall with her arms crossed and watches him come.

He passes her, and they look at each other for one beat, then two.

He keeps walking, and the corner of her mouth moves.

At Roy's Diner the whole room sits frozen at the counter with the television still going.

BUCK, the regular in the feed cap, lets out one hard laugh and slaps the counter.

Behind the counter the COOK checks the little meter on the gas line, then turns the flat-top burners up, every one of them, all the way.

INT. FRONTIER AEROSPACE, VESS'S OFFICE - NIGHT

Mira Vess, forties, Frontier's COO, sits behind a clean desk in a glass office with her jacket still on and a closed folder squared in front of her. She does not get up.

Administrator J. Pell, fifties, lanyard and an easy smile, comes in ahead of two federal marshals and leaves them at the door.

PELL:
Mira. Thanks for staying, I know it's late and everyone's worn out.

PELL:
Walk me down to the room, we'll send the recall up together, and this turns into a good night for everybody.

Vess folds her hands on the folder and looks up at him.

VESS:
There is no override. The ship answers its crew.

PELL:
Everybody comes home tonight. That's the whole idea here.

VESS:
You built the compliance regime, Administrator. Nothing at this company moves without a signature. You know that better than anyone.

She opens the folder, turns the top page around to face him, and slides it across.

The page shows a cargo weighed a second time and signed off, with a correction added in the margin.

She lays the next one down. It is a site inspection log, it reads exceeds requirement, and his signature is at the bottom.

She lays the last one down. It is a yellow inspection tag, a carbon copy, stamped INSPECTED and signed J. PELL, with a photograph clipped to the corner.

His name is at the bottom of the first page and the log, his initials sit beside the correction, his signature is on the tag, and all four are in his own hand.

Pell sets one finger on the tag and turns the photograph toward himself.

PELL:
You scheduled—

He stops with the word half out of his mouth. His finger stays on the tag.

Vess watches his hand a moment, then keeps her eyes on him.

VESS:
Take it public, Administrator. All of it. Walk them through the program you ran, the cargo you certified, the shop you praised. Somebody's name ends up in the story. Count the signatures and tell me whose.

She stands, comes around the desk, and crosses behind him to the door.

VESS:
You wanted the company to cooperate. The company cooperated. The country didn't.

She walks out through the marshals at the door, unhurried, and no one stops her.

Pell stays where he is. The pages lie in a row on the desk, all of them turned to face her empty chair.

After a moment he draws the visitor's chair out, sits down in front of them, and does not touch anything.

INT. FRONTIER AEROSPACE, HALE'S OFFICE - NIGHT

In his dark office at Frontier, Magnus Hale sits alone at the desk in a coat over rolled sleeves, fifties, the phone lighting his face.

He types two words into the empty box and holds his thumb over the button without pressing it.

His thumb comes down, and the post goes up on the screen, Look up.

He turns the phone face down on the desk and keeps his hand flat on top of it.

At Roy's Diner, the phone by the register buzzes and walks itself an inch across the counter.

Earlene, sixties, an order pad in her apron, picks it up and reads the screen.

EARLENE:
Look up, it says.

She holds the phone up over the pass, and the cook wipes his hands and comes around the counter to the front window.

Out at the Dawes place near Kearney, Danny stands on the porch in a coat thrown over his shirt, fifties, Cricket's boy.

He puts his hand on the porch light switch and works it, off and on twice, a pause, then off and on twice again.

His phone buzzes in the coat pocket, and he gets it up to his ear without stopping the switch.

JOSS (RADIO):
That you working it, or is that thing on a timer.

DANNY:
It's me.

Down the section road, a set of truck headlights flashes back at him, twice and twice.

Joss Reed, twenty-six, the Frontier dock hand from the night shop, hangs half out of the cab and keeps flicking the brights.

A farmhouse across the valley comes on, then one past it, some of them steady and some blinking, spreading along the fence lines.

At the county ballpark, the groundskeeper stands at the breaker panel under the bleachers and throws whole banks of the tower lights, off and on, off and on.

From high over the state, whole suburb grids pulse on and off, block by block.

The interstates run bright with hazard flashers, and out past them the dark country keeps filling in, one porch at a time.

In a grid control room, an operator watches the load line on the wall screen climb straight up and off the top of the chart, and he leans into his headset.

OPERATOR:
That's more draw than the whole state used to pull on the Fourth. Where's this even coming from?

Back at the diner window, Buck leans up in his feed cap and watches the porch light on his own house, a block down, blink off and on again.

BUCK:
Good.

On the Moon, the seven of them sit around the card table on the gray flat, and Stitch has the next hand half dealt out in his glove.

Stitch stops with a card still pinched in his glove and tips his helmet back toward the Earth.

STITCH:
Y'all.

Seven visors tilt back at once.

On the night side of the Earth, light crawls across the black in slow waves, whole coastlines brightening and going dark again.

Nobody says anything for a long time, and the cards hang forgotten in Stitch's glove.

At the grill, without looking away from the Earth, Gunny reaches over and turns the burner down low.

EXT. TRANQUILITY BASE - LUNAR DAY

On the rise Brandt stands with his two crew behind him, the six flags and the little camp laid out in the dust below.

At the grill GUNNY, Tibbs, seventy-one, in a yellowed suit, brings a sealed press down over the grate and lifts it away.

A burger comes up under the glass of the press, plated and cooked, and Gunny slides it onto a paper plate.

Brandt watches it through his visor with the loop keyed open.

BRANDT:
...is that a burger?

In a control room a young controller claps a hand over his mouth and the sound gets past it anyway.

The back row of consoles goes over one after another until the whole floor is shaking with it.

Along the bottom of broadcasts in forty languages the same three words scroll past.

On the rise Brandt straightens, keys the loop, and takes his time with it.

BRANDT:
Geneva, Harmony One. Site survey complete. There is nothing at Tranquility to retrieve. There is a color guard, on station, under national colors. Harmony One stands down.

The loop gives back Geneva static and nothing else.

In Roy's Diner the cook works the flat-top with both hands, sliding out burgers faster than anybody at the counter asked for.

A trucker digs for his wallet and the cook waves him off without looking up from the grill.

BUCK, seventies, feed cap, lifts his coffee cup an inch toward the TV in the corner and holds it up there.

In a square in Warsaw a crowd packed around a screen comes apart, arms over their heads, howling.

At a lectern a Geneva coordinator tries to get through his statement while the room laughs over every word he lands.

In the White House briefing room the press secretary takes hold of both sides of the podium and hangs on.

PRESS SECRETARY:
We're still getting information. The situation has, it's evolved.

Back on the Moon Gunny turns from the grill with the plate balanced on the end of the long spatula.

He reaches it out across the three meters of dust between the camp and the rise and holds the blade level for Brandt.

Brandt looks at it a second, then lifts the burger off the blade with his glove.

Behind the glass Lindqvist's shoulders are going. No sound comes through.

Gunny looks over at Shen, standing off on his own with his arms folded.

GUNNY:
You want one or no.

Shen does not move.

Gunny plates another one anyway, carries it to the card table, and sets it down at the empty fourth chair, facing out at Shen.

The burger sits there in front of the empty chair.

Shen looks at it once and looks off the other way.

Gunny wipes his glove down his leg and works a folded photocopy out of a chest pocket.

He gets it open and reads off of it, slow, an old man with small print.

GUNNY:
It ought to be solemnized with pomp and parade, with shows, games, sports, guns, bells, bonfires and illuminations, from one end of this continent to the other, from this time forward, forevermore.

Stitch, still down in his chair, tips his head back at the black over them.

STITCH:
Two hundred and fifty years, and here we all are, a good bit further out than he probably figured.

Cricket keys the loop toward home.

CRICKET:
Tito Alvarez. You built the tubes. Count us down.

In a Nebraska barn TITO, twenty-four, welder's cap shoved back, leans in to a microphone clamped on a work light, the feed glowing on a laptop beside him.

TITO:
Tres. Dos. Uno.

The first shell rides a hard straight spark up off the surface and breaks RED, a round ball that opens and keeps opening, nothing in the vacuum to slow it, and no sound at all.

The second one breaks WHITE, rings opening inside of rings, silent, spreading out over the ring of flags.

Cricket crosses to the first flag at the center on its old pole and keys the loop out to the whole lit face of the Earth.

CRICKET:
It's Independence Day.

The planet stays quiet on the loop for a beat.

CRICKET:
God bless America.

The third shell breaks BLUE-WHITE dead center over the ring and swells out until it fills the whole frame.

The picture goes to white and holds there, and no sound comes.

EXT. TRANQUILITY BASE - LUNAR DAY (DAYS LATER)

Days later, the crew loads out below the ring of flags, the lander squatting on the pad with its cargo door hung open on the hinge the landing bent.

DUTCH, Haas, seventy-six, a binder open in one glove, runs a finger down a column and stops on it.

DUTCH:
Latch light's amber. Door won't seat.

The cargo door stands a hand's width proud of its frame. Cricket sets a shoulder into it and it gives back nothing.

DUTCH:
The ship's back overhead in eleven minutes. Miss that and we haven't got the air to wait on the next pass.

Dutch closes the binder and looks at the gap in the door.

DUTCH:
It has to be held shut from outside while the latches run. Somebody on the bar, with his weight on it.

Cricket takes the pry bar off the deck before Dutch has the sentence finished.

He sets the bar under the door's lip, plants his boots, and puts his whole weight down onto it.

The door drops the last of the way into its frame.

The latches walk shut along the seam, one and then the next.

In the cabin Brandt puts a glove flat against the window.

BRANDT:
Dawes --

Cricket keeps his weight on the bar and does not look up.

CRICKET:
GO.

The ascent engine lights under the stage, a hard white spark, and no sound comes.

The lander lifts off the pad and climbs, up and then over, and the dust settles back down in slow sheets.

Cricket stands alone at the ring of flags and holds a salute.

He holds it until the spark is one bright point among the stars.

He lowers the hand, turns, and walks back toward the flags, his boots falling in with the hundreds of prints already there.

In the climbing cabin Stitch reaches to the window and raps the glass with a knuckle, two, a pause, then two.

Down on the surface Cricket sits on the fender of the parked rover and keys his glove against it, two, a pause, then two.

In the cabin a foil bundle goes from glove to glove down the row, gone cold.

Lindqvist works one loose and holds it out to Shen, wedged in beside him.

Shen looks at it a moment, takes it, peels the foil back, and eats.

Nobody says anything about it.

Dutch chews and starts penciling a figure on the smoothed-out foil.

Months later, Roy's Diner is half full and the TV in the corner runs C-SPAN, a vote board filling in green.

ON THE SCREEN -- a chyron reads RESTORATION OF FLIGHT STATUS ACT PASSES 98 TO 2. BACKUP CREWS OF THE APOLLO PROGRAM ENTERED INTO THE ROLLS.

Buck sits at the counter with his cup and watches the board fill.

BUCK:
Who were the two?

Earlene tops off his cup without looking at him.

EARLENE:
Does it matter?

BUCK:
I'd like to know their addresses is all.

The screen cuts to a photo of a man with a lanyard, a chyron under it that reads ACCORD ENFORCEMENT INQUIRY NAMES SPECIAL ADMINISTRATOR, ADMINISTRATION COOPERATING FULLY.

On the wall behind the register, four screw holes sit empty above the gas line where a meter used to be bolted.

In a barn near Kearney, DANNY, Dawes, fifty, sits at a radio rig in a headset with a new spiral notebook open, his own hand on the spine.

DANNY:
Net's open. Tuesday, nineteen-oh-two local.

GUNNY (RADIO):
Copy.

DUTCH (RADIO):
Here.

STITCH (RADIO):
On time for once, son.

The rig hisses. A long pause runs out, three seconds of it, the signal gone all the way out and back.

CRICKET (RADIO):
Tranquility. Reading you loud and clear.

STITCH (RADIO):
Boy believes we went now, mind. He just don't believe the flags kept their color. Says y'all swapped 'em.

The rig hisses again, three more seconds of it.

CRICKET (RADIO):
Hm.

Danny grins at the rig and writes the time down in the log.

ON THE FRIDGE -- Danny slides a pay stub under a magnet and squares it with his thumb. It reads DAWES, E., RANGER (FIRST), TRANQUILITY BASE NATIONAL HISTORIC PARK, and a figure of $4,017.62.

On the Moon a sign stands staked in the dust that reads TRANQUILITY BASE NATIONAL HISTORIC PARK, ESTABLISHED JULY 4, RANGER STATION NO. 1.

A small hab sits off the original site with resupply pods lined up beside it.

The six flags stand in their ring, their colors lit by the light coming off the Earth.

Over the hab, on a workshop pole, the flag with fifty-one stars hangs still.

Cricket walks out to the ring in a suit patched at the knee, a park ranger's patch on his chest.

He goes around the ring and gives each staff one firm pull.

He finishes at the flag at the center on its old pole and looks up.

The Earth hangs full above him with its night side turned his way.

Cricket raises one glove all the way up and waves.

Nothing answers for a moment.

Then a city flickers on the dark face of the Earth, and then another one beside it.

Whole coastlines come up pulsing, two and a pause and two, the wave rolling west across the night, one city into the next and one sea to the next.

Cricket holds his glove up, and the Earth keeps answering, and the flags hold their colors in the black.

FADE OUT.

THE END.

